{"title_page": "The Buzz on Maggie", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Buzz on Maggie\n| image                = The Buzz on Maggie.png\n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{unbulleted list|[[Comedy series|Comedy]]|[[Slapstick]]}}\n| runtime              = 22 minutes\n| creator              = [[Dave Polsky]]\n| executive_producer   = {{unbulleted list|Dave Polsky|Dave Wasson|Laura Perkins Brittain (co-executive)}}\n| theme_music_composer = {{unbulleted list|[[Bob Thiele Jr.]]|Dillon O'Brian}}\n| director             = [[Dave Wasson]]\n| voices               = {{unbulleted list|[[Jessica DiCicco]]|[[David Kaufman (actor)|David Kaufman]]|[[Thom Adcox-Hernandez|Thom Adcox]]|[[Cree Summer]]|[[Brian Doyle-Murray]]|[[Susan Tolsky]]}}\n| opentheme            = \"Just the Way I Am\" by [[Skye Sweetnam]]\n| composer             = [[Adam Berry]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| network              = [[Disney Channel]]\n| picture_format       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[SDTV]])\n*[[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FXCYTBKqgYA=youtube|title=Proof that \"The Buzz on Maggie\" Was Made in Widescreen|work=[[YouTube]]|publisher=[[Google]]}}</ref>)\n}}\n| company              = [[Disney Television Animation|Walt Disney Television Animation]]\n| distributor          = [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television|Buena Vista Television]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2005|6|17}} \n| last_aired           = {{End date|2006|5|27}}\n| num_seasons          = 1 \n| num_episodes         = 21 (42 segments)\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n}}\n'''''The Buzz on Maggie''''' is an American [[cartoon series|animated television series]] created by [[Dave Polsky]] for [[Disney Channel]]. The series centers on an ambitious and expressive [[Preadolescence|tween]] [[fly]] named Maggie Pesky and her family and friends. The show is set in Stickyfeet, a city for insects located in a [[landfill|dump]]. While conceptualizing the series, Polsky wanted it to contain a playful aspect at adolescence and director [[Dave Wasson]] formed the overall look of the characters, being heavily influenced by early [[Walt Disney]] cartoon shorts. ''The Buzz on Maggie'' was Disney's first series to be fully animated in [[Adobe Flash]], a process done by [[Bardel Entertainment]] and [[Future Thought Productions]].\n\n''The Buzz on Maggie'' premiered on June 17, 2005, and aired its final episode on May 27, 2006, concluding its only season. The series received positive reviews from television critics, many of whom praised its humor, voice acting and writing. The theme song \u201cJust the Way I Am\u201d, performed by Canadian singer [[Skye Sweetnam]], was also met with critical praise and a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nomination in 2006. During its run, ''The Buzz on Maggie'' also received an [[Annie Award]] nomination for its character design.\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Maggie and Rayna.jpg|left|220px|The main characters, Maggie (left) and her best friend Rayna (right).|thumb]]\n''The Buzz on Maggie'' follows Maggie Pesky ([[Jessica DiCicco]]), an expressive 13-year-old fly and her family; parents Chauncey ([[Brian Doyle-Murray]]) and Frieda ([[Susan Tolsky]]);<ref>{{Cite episode| title = Faking History| series = The Buzz on Maggie| serieslink =| credits = Stein, Robin J; Grieb, Wendy; Wasson, Dave| network = [[Disney Channel]]| airdate = March 4, 2006| season = 1| number = 17a| time = 3:46 to 4:06| quote = '''Mrs. Pesky''': Oh hello, Mr. Bugspit! I'm Frieda. [...] '''Mr. Pesky''': Come in, Cornelius. I'm Chauncey Pesky.}}</ref> brothers Aldrin ([[David Kaufman (actor)|David Kaufman]]) and Pupert ([[Thom Adcox-Hernandez|Thom Adcox]]); and sister Bella ([[Tara Strong]]), who is still a [[maggot]]. The family resides in an old milk carton in a suburban fly metropolis called Stickyfeet, which is located in a [[landfill|dump]].<ref name=\"awn\"/><ref name=\"dmn\"/> Maggie has an ambitious and adventurous personality and aspires to become a rock star.<ref name=\"dmn\"/> Her approach to life often suffers unexpected consequences that puts herself in jeopardy, as she often follows her own impulses although they go against the rules or her parents' wishes.<ref name=\"shj\"/><ref name=\"tpi\"/> However, she ultimately learns her lesson,<ref name=\"shj\"/> which was one of the core themes for the show's conception.<ref name=\"awn\"/>\n\nMaggie attends a [[middle school|junior high school]] called Buzzdale Academy with her best friend Rayna Cartflight ([[Cree Summer]]) and [[archenemy|nemesis]] Dawn Swatworthy (Tara Strong). The school's staff include the sneaky Principal Peststrip ([[Jeff Bennett]]), pompous Mr. Bugspit ([[Curtis Armstrong]]) and gruff Mrs. Wingston ([[Candi Milo]]).<ref name=\"awn\"/> ''The Buzz on Maggie'' uses a [[slapstick]] comedy style and relies slightly on [[gross-out humor]].<ref name=\"ljw\"/> It also includes several insect aspects, such as flies' appetite for spoiled and rotten food.<ref name=\"ljw\"/><ref name=\"tpi\"/> The show features various references to [[popular culture|pop culture]] and common themes, such as sibling rivalry and [[peer pressure]], from a fly's point of view.<ref name=\"tpi\"/>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:JessicaDiCicco.jpg|thumb|upright|Newcomer [[Jessica DiCicco]] provided the voice of Maggie.]]\nThe concept of ''The Buzz on Maggie'' was created by [[Dave Polsky]], a former writer on ''[[Scary Movie 2]]'' and ''[[South Park]]''.<ref name=\"anmag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/maggie-begins-buzzing-on-disney/ |title=Maggie Begins Buzzing on Disney |work=[[Animation Magazine]] |date=June 17, 2005 |last=Zahed |first=Ramin |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119010723/http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/maggie-begins-buzzing-on-disney/ |archivedate=November 19, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In an early interview for [[Animation World Network]], he explained that the series utilizes a playful aspect at adolescence, naming it \"individuality vs. conformity\".<ref name=\"awn\"/> He said, \"Maggie must learn how to pursue her agenda without alienating those she cares about. More often than not, Maggie learns that it is difficult to negotiate life on her terms without burning bridges.\"<ref name=\"awn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/news/television/disneys-buzz-maggie-flies-debutes-disney-channel |title=Disney's ''The Buzz on Maggie'' Flies Debutes on Disney Channel |last=Baisley |first=Sarah |date=June 17, 2005 |work=[[Animation World Network]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140417095950/http://www.awn.com/news/television/disneys-buzz-maggie-flies-debutes-disney-channel |archivedate=April 17, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Dave Wasson]], the creator of the animated series ''[[Time Squad]]'', served as the director, and executively produced the series with Polsky, while Laura Perkins Brittain was the co-executive producer.<ref name=\"awn\"/>\n\nWasson formed Maggie's character design and supported the use of [[Adobe Flash]] for animating the series. He told ''[[Animation Magazine]]'' that he was convinced Flash was a \"good way to go\" as he had had previous experience with the program, such as commercials and short films.<ref name=\"anmag\"/> The series became Disney's first to be fully animated in Flash.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/852665411.html?dids=852665411:852665411&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+12%2C+2005&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=ON+THIS+WEEK%3A+JUNE+12-18&pqatl=google|title=On this Week: June 12\u201318|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|date=June 12, 2005|accessdate=March 29, 2012|page=Y.03}}</ref> Following the cancellation of [[Kids' WB]]'s ''[[\u00a1Mucha Lucha!]]'', many animators from that series were hired to work on ''The Buzz on Maggie''.<ref name=\"anmag\"/> For the character designs, Wasson was heavily influenced by early cartoon shorts by [[Tex Avery]], [[Warner Bros.]] and [[Walt Disney]]. He noted that the characters in ''The Buzz on Maggie'' have \"a lot of 1930s touches\" and wear white gloves, which is a direct homage to the cartoon shorts.<ref name=\"anmag\"/> The characters also have [[anime]]-inspired designs with oversized heads and large eyes.<ref name=\"am\"/> Wasson stated that the concept of Maggie living in a dump gave him a \"lot of visual opportunities\".<ref name=\"anmag\"/> [[Jorge Gutierrez (animator)|Jorge Gutierrez]] supervised the character design and Roman Laney supervised location and prop design in addition to background paint. The animation was done by [[Bardel Entertainment]] and [[Future Thought Productions]].<ref name=\"awn\"/><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/futurethoughtanimation/thatdarnjesus/prweb558627.htm|title=Future Thought Flashes onto the Big Screen at MIPCOM|date=October 5, 2007|location=San Jose, California|publisher=[[PR Web]]|accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe series' theme song \"Just the Way I Am\" was composed by [[Bob Thiele Jr.]] and Dillon O'Brian, and performed by Canadian singer [[Skye Sweetnam]].<ref name=\"awn\"/> The song is about pride, acceptance and empowerment.<ref name=\"ljw\"/> [[Adam Berry]] did the show's [[film score|score]].<ref name=\"awn\"/> [[Charlie Adler]] voice directed ''The Buzz on Maggie'' and helmed [[voice casting]] with Jamie Thomason.<ref name=\"awn\"/> Newcomer [[Jessica DiCicco]] was cast as Maggie,<ref name=\"tpi\"/> her first main role on a television series, preceding her role on ''[[Loonatics Unleashed]]'', which premiered the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/loonatics-cast-unleashed/|title=''Loonatics'' Cast Unleashed|work=Animation Magazine|last=Ball|first=Ryan|date=June 6, 2005|accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref> The rest of the main cast included [[David Kaufman (actor)|David Kaufman]], [[Thom Adcox]], [[Cree Summer]], [[Brian Doyle-Murray]] and [[Susan Tolsky]].<ref name=\"awn\"/> [[Tara Strong]] voiced Maggie's nemesis Dawn, among other minor characters.<ref name=\"awn\"/> The series had a few guest voice actors, such as [[Laraine Newman]], [[Paul Rodriguez (actor) |Paul Rodriguez]], and [[Jon Polito]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/71769-Ladybugged.html|title=Ladybugged (2005)|publisher=[[Big Cartoon Database]]|accessdate=July 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/77553-Those_Pesky_Roaches.html|title=Those Pesky Roaches (2005)|publisher=Big Cartoon Database|accessdate=July 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''The Buzz on Maggie'' premiered on Disney Channel on Friday June 17, 2005, At 8:00PM And 8:30PM with two back-to-back episodes.<ref name=\"slpd\"/><ref name=\"anmag\"/> The next week, it moved to its regular timeslot in the channel's weekend block.<ref name=\"tpi\"/><ref name=\"anmag\"/> Each half-hour episode consists of two different segments.<ref name=\"dmn\"/> ''The Buzz on Maggie'' aired for one season, comprising 21 half-hour episodes. The final episode, containing the segments \"Synchronized Flying\" and \"Roach Hotel\", aired on May 27, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/detail/tv-show.aspx?tvobjectid=194683&more=ucepisodelist&episodeid=5567075|title=Episode Detail: Synchronized Flying; Roach Hotel&nbsp;\u2013 ''The Buzz on Maggie''|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 2005, ''The Buzz on Maggie'' was picked up by sister network [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref name=\"am\"/> The network began airing reruns of the show from September 17, 2005, to January 21, 2006 on the Saturday morning block [[ABC Kids (United States)|ABC Kids]].<ref name=\"ABCKids\">{{cite press release|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=090705_11|title=ABC Kids premieres new fall season Saturday, September 17, on the ABC Television Network|publisher=ABC Medianet|date=September 7, 2005|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> According to [[Nielsen Media Research]], the ABC premiere acquired a 1.6 rating in the Kids 2\u201311 demographic, and a 1.4 rating in Tweens 9\u201314, as well as a 7% share in both demographics.<ref name=\"abcrating\"/> The premiere was that timeslot's highest-rated broadcast in nearly three months across the block's three key demographics, Kids 2\u201311, Kids 6\u201311 and Tweens 9\u201314.<ref name=\"abcrating\">{{cite press release|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=092205_06|title=Ratings Report for ABC Kids For Saturday September 17, 2005|publisher=ABC Medianet|accessdate=March 31, 2012|date=September 22, 2005}}</ref> During the ABC Kids broadcasts, the series carried an [[E/I]] designation.<ref name=\"ABCKids\"/>\n\n==Episodes==\nAll episodes were directed by [[Dave Wasson]].\n{{Episode table|background=1254A4|overall=|title=|writer=|airdate=|prodcode=|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = The Flyinator\"<hr>\"Ladybugged \n| WrittenBy       = Rachel Duguay<hr>Alicia Sky Varinaitis\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|6|17}}\n| ProdCode        = 103\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''The Flyinator'''\": When Maggie can't see the same movies as Aldrin she starts trying to be better than he is; she sneaks into an R-rated movie to be better than he is.<hr>\"'''Ladybugged'''\": When Maggie thinks up a theme for the school dance, it is quickly threatened by a new student, who apparently has a better theme.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| Title           = Funball\"<hr>\"The Science Whatchamacallit\n| WrittenBy       = Dan Fybel and Rich Rinaldi<hr>Rachel Duguay\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|6|17}}\n| ProdCode        = 102\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Funball'''\": Maggie devises a new game for her little brother Pupert to play so he can beat Aldrin at something, but when Aldrin starts to get the hang of the game things take an unexpected turn for the worse.<hr>\"'''The Science Whatchamacallit'''\": Maggie and Rayna try to get their science partners who are really smart to do all the work for an assignment, but when it comes time to present the projects something unexpected happens.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| Title           = The Candidate\"<hr>\"Germy\n| WrittenBy       = Rachelle Romberg<hr>[[Dave Polsky]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|6|24}}\n| ProdCode        = 101\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''The Candidate'''\": The school bully faces some competition for the title of Homecoming Queen when Maggie gives an ugly butterfly named Maria a makeover.<hr>\"'''Germy'''\": When Maggie wants to bring home a pet germ, her dad won't let her so she sneaks it home, but faces a problem with training especially when Maggie's parents find out. \n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| Title           = Lunch Lady\"<hr>\"Love Stinks\n| WrittenBy       = Dan Fybel and Rich Rinaldi<hr>Laura Perkins Brittain\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|7|1}}\n| ProdCode        = 104\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Lunch Lady'''\": Maggie accidentally gets the lunch lady to quit, causing the parents to take over the school.<hr>\"'''Love Stinks'''\": Maggie goes on a date with a stinkbug even though she doesn't want to.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| Title           = The Price of Fame\"<hr>\"King Flear\n| WrittenBy       = Rachelle Romberg<hr>Manny Basanese\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|7|8}}\n| ProdCode        = 105\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''The Price of Fame'''\": Maggie suggests that Pupert uses music to impress a girl.<hr>\"'''King Flear'''\": Maggie directs her classmates in a play for a drama competition.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| Title           = Rottingmuck Ranch\"<hr>\"Bella Con Carny\n| WrittenBy       = Danny Warren and Josh Lynn<hr>Chris Bowman\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|7|15}}\n| ProdCode        = 110\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Rottingmuck Ranch'''\": Maggie wants to be Uncle Zeb's favorite relative again.<hr>\"'''Bella Con Carny'''\": Maggie has to spend bonding time with her little sister after her mom is convinced Maggie doesn't spend enough time with Bella.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| Title           = Bugsitting\"<hr>\"Le Termite\n| WrittenBy       = Laura Perkins Brittain<hr>Rachel Duguay\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|7|22}}\n| ProdCode        = 107\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Bugsitting'''\": Maggie has to babysit, which conflicts with a promise she made to Pupert.<hr>\"'''Le Termite'''\": Maggie gets a job as a maid at a gourmet restaurant, but tells her parents that she is the head chef.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| Title           = Pieface\"<hr>\"The Hangout\n| WrittenBy       = Dan Fybel and Rich Rinaldi<hr>Laura Perkins Brittain\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|8|5}}\n| ProdCode        = 108\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Pieface'''\": Maggie is determined to hit Principal Pestrip in the face with a pie as a homecoming prank.<hr>\"'''The Hangout'''\": Maggie and her brothers vie for control of her new hangout.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 9\n| Title           = Slumber Party\"<hr>\"Spelling Bees\n| WrittenBy       = Will Berson<hr>Manny Basanese\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|8|13}}\n| ProdCode        = 106\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Slumber Party'''\": Maggie's parents decide to leave Maggie in charge of Pupert while they take Aldrin to a big flyball game. Unbeknownst to her parents, Maggie hosts a slumber party to which Rayna invites some nocturnal guests.<hr>\"'''Spelling Bees'''\": Maggie's favorite spelling team are holding auditions for a new speller, but only accepts famous bees, leaving Maggie to disguise herself as one.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 10\n| Title           = The Usual Insects\"<hr>\"Sister Act\n| WrittenBy       = Chris Bowman<hr>Katherine Butler\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|9|17}}\n| ProdCode        = 111\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''The Usual Insects'''\": Maggie and her friends' school records are sabotaged when Dawn becomes office assistant.<hr>\"'''Sister Act'''\": Maggie and her baby sister Bella audition for a baby food commercial.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 11\n| Title           = Hooligans\"<hr>\"Scum Bites\n| WrittenBy       = Julie Chambers and David Chambers<hr>Robin J. Stein\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|9|24}}\n| ProdCode        = 116\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Hooligans'''\": Maggie reports a school bully by tattling to his parents.<hr>\"'''Scum Bites'''\": Maggie challenges Dawn on the school's charity fund drive selling Scum Bites candy.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 12\n| Title           = The Big Score\"<hr>\"Scare Wars\n| WrittenBy       = Dan Fybel and Rich Rinaldi<hr>Rachel Duguay\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|10|22}}\n| ProdCode        = 113\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''The Big Score'''\": Maggie and her friends head to the human world to go trick-or-treating.<hr>\"'''Scare Wars'''\": The Pesky children attempt to out scare one another and this year Maggie is the target.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 13\n| Title           = Metamorpho Sis\"<hr>\"Radio Free Buzzdale\n| WrittenBy       = Alicia Sky Varinaitis<hr>Chris Bowman\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|11|12}}\n| ProdCode        = 114\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Metamorpho Sis'''\": Maggie volunteers to become a child's mentor, but has some regrets about the decision when she is matched up with a cranky cocoon.<hr>\"'''Radio Free Buzzdale'''\": Maggie joins Principal Peststrip's crusade to stop an anonymous kid DJ who has gained unauthorized access to the school's radio station.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 14\n| Title           = Those Pesky Roaches\"<hr>\"Bugtillion\n| WrittenBy       = Beth Seriff and Geoff Tarson<hr>Lloyd Garver\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|12|17}}\n| ProdCode        = 115\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Those Pesky Roaches'''\": When Maggie and her brothers go on strike for bigger allowances, their parents hire roaches to do their chores for them.<hr>\"'''Bugtillion'''\": When Rayna is rejected for Bugtillion classes, Maggie tries out herself as part of a plot to avenge her friend.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 15\n| Title           = Hot for Tutor\"<hr>\"Sick Days, Inc.\n| WrittenBy       = Dan Fybel and Rich Rinaldi<hr>Sharon Schatz Rosenthal\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2006|1|7}}\n| ProdCode        = 112\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Hot for Tutor'''\": Maggie and Rayna both fall for the same math tutor.<hr>\"'''Sick Days, Inc.'''\": Maggie and Rayna sell kits that help students pretend that they are sick to raise money for tickets to a rock concert.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 16\n| Title           = Scout of Order\"<hr>\"Ant Mines\n| WrittenBy       = Sharon Schatz Rosenthal<hr>Robin J. Stein\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2006|2|11}}\n| ProdCode        = 109\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Scout of Order'''\": Maggie falls for Pupert's scout headmaster.<hr>\"'''Ant Mines'''\": Maggie writes a story on the allegedly oppressed conditions of some ants in a human kid's ant farm for the school newspaper, but when she finds out that their lives are better than what she expected, she writes a false article.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 17\n| Title           = Faking History\"<hr>\"Bugs on the Brink\n| WrittenBy       = Robin J. Stein<hr>Lloyd Garver\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2006|3|4}}\n| ProdCode        = 118\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Faking History'''\": Maggie cuts corners on her history project so that she can enjoy spring break, but matters are complicated when her father befriends her history teacher.<hr>\"'''Bugs on the Brink'''\": When humans threaten to tear down Stickyfeet to make way for a strip mall, Maggie disguises Rayna as an endangered beetle.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 18\n| Title           = Training Day\"<hr>\"Honey Striper\n| WrittenBy       = Dan Fybel and Rich Rinaldi<hr>Sharon Schatz Rosenthal\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2006|3|18}}\n| ProdCode        = 117\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Training Day'''\": When Aldrin injures his wing while winning a scooter for Maggie, Maggie agrees to do all his chores out of guilt while nursing him back to health in time for his team's football game.<hr>\"'''Honey Striper'''\": Maggie and Rayna volunteer to work in a hospital in order to visit an injured rock star.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 19\n| Title           = Raccooooon!\"<hr>\"Best Best Friends\n| WrittenBy       = Brandon Sawyer<hr>Nina Bargiel and Jeremy Bargiel\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2006|4|22}}\n| ProdCode        = 119\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Raccooooon!'''\": A raccoon causes trouble for the citizens of Stickyfeet.<hr>\"'''Best Best Friend'''\": Rayna's old best friend moves to Stickyfeet, driving a wedge between Rayna and Maggie.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 20\n| Title           = Peskys Unclogged\"<hr>\"Club Hopping\n| WrittenBy       = Katherine Butler<hr>Manny Basanese\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2006|5|6}}\n| ProdCode        = 120\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Peskys Unclogged'''\": Maggie is embarrassed when her family is all set to demonstrate the Pesky age-old tradition of clogging on a local cable TV network.<hr>\"'''Club Hopping'''\": Maggie joins every club in her school to avoid a math test.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 21\n| Title           = Synchronized Flying\"<hr>\"Roach Hotel\n| WrittenBy       = Brooke Cadorette<hr>Chris Bowman\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2006|5|27}}\n| ProdCode        = 121\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Synchronized Flying'''\": Maggie tries everything except the truth to avoid being Rayna's synchronized flying partner.<hr>\"'''Roach Hotel'''\": Aldrin tries to sabotage the family vacation that was planned by Maggie.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n{{quotebox|align=right|width=20%|quote=\"It's the voices ... that hit the humor home, from Jessica DiCicco in the starring role to Cree Summer's wonderfully deadpan pal Rayna to the recognizable gruffness of Brian Doyle-Murray as her dad. Let's hope the gang from Stickyfeet stays.\"|source=\u2014Roger Catlin, ''[[Hartford Courant]]''<ref name=\"Hartford\"/>}}\n''The Buzz on Maggie'' received positive reviews from television critics. Jeff Hidek of ''[[Star-News]]'' viewed it as \"''[[Miss Spider's Sunny Patch Friends]]'' meets ''[[The Proud Family]]''\" and named it \"by far the most entertaining of this summer's new offerings\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7xBPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qB8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=1474,3008857&dq=the-buzz-on-maggie&hl=en|title=Monkeys, bugs and bears try to get kids' attention|last=Hidek|first=Jeff|date=June 26, 2005|work=[[Star-News]]|publisher=[[Halifax Media Group]]|volume=138|page=17|number=255|accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref> Roger Catlin of ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' wrote that it stands out from other shows on Disney Channel by \"being a little sassy and sharp, and a whole lot funnier than most of [the channel's] stuff\".<ref name=\"Hartford\"/> He wrote that the channel \"gets back into the race dominated by Cartoon Network offerings ... and a Nickelodeon roster ... with an offering just as hip and well designed\".<ref name=\"Hartford\"/> Catlin commended the voice acting and the \"sharp\" writing, stating that the former factor \"hit[s] the humor home\".<ref name=\"Hartford\">{{cite news |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%2010ACC838E3150F17%20)&p_docid=10ACC838E3150F17&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10ACC838E3150F17&f_openurl=yes&p |title=Disney Makes Strong Step with ''Maggie'' on Cartoon Night |work=[[Hartford Courant]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |last=Catlin |first=Roger |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708205858/http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date%3AD&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id%3D%28%2010ACC838E3150F17%20%29&p_docid=10ACC838E3150F17&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10ACC838E3150F17&f_openurl=yes&p |archivedate=July 8, 2019 |date=June 17, 2005 |page=D10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' critic David Hiltbrand noted that although the show includes \"a little\" gross-out humor, \"it's reasonably tasteful by adolescent standards\".<ref name=\"tpi\"/> He concluded, \"The animation ... is a little substandard, but the premise is nicely maintained.\"<ref name=\"tpi\">{{cite news |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%2010ACE4F7611F1079%20)&p_docid=10ACE4F7611F1079&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10ACE4F7611F1079&f_openurl=yes&p |title=Fly cartoon, and one that doesn't take off&nbsp;\u2013 ''Juniper Lee'': Lazy, loud and laughless |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]] |last=Hiltbrand |first=David |date=June 17, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708210006/http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date%3AD&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id%3D%28%2010ACE4F7611F1079%20%29&p_docid=10ACE4F7611F1079&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10ACE4F7611F1079&f_openurl=yes&p |archivedate=July 8, 2019 |page=E12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[AllMovie]]'s Hal Erickson deemed the fly concept unoriginal, but said that the show \"set[s] itself apart from such earlier endeavors\".<ref name=\"am\"/> Erickson regarded Maggie's \"strong, forceful attitude\" a positive role model for kids.<ref name=\"am\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-buzz-on-maggie-animated-tv-series-v339335|title=''The Buzz on Maggie'' <nowiki>[</nowiki>Animated TV Series<nowiki>]</nowiki>|work=[[AllMovie]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|last=Erickson|first=Hal|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> A critic for ''[[Observer-Reporter]]'' deemed it \"suitably silly\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%2010ACE4F7611F1079%20)&p_docid=10ACE4F7611F1079&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10ACE4F7611F1079&f_openurl=yes&p |title=No Headline |work=[[Observer-Reporter]] |publisher=Observer Publishing Company |date=June 17, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708210121/http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date%3AD&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id%3D%28%2010ACA9CFA23F3056%20%29&p_docid=10ACA9CFA23F3056&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10ACA9CFA23F3056&f_openurl=yes&p |archivedate=July 8, 2019 |page=E4 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Robert Lloyd of ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \"delightful\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/oct/30/entertainment/ca-cartoons30|title=New kids on the comic bloc|date=October 30, 2005|last=Lloyd|first=Robert|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=Tribune Company|accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of its premiere, Gail Pennington of ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' named the show one of the \"Tops of the night\".<ref name=\"slpd\">{{cite news |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%2010ACE00E325E3ECB%20)&p_docid=10ACE00E325E3ECB&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10ACE00E325E3ECB&f_openurl=yes&p |title=Critic's Pick |last=Pennington |first=Gail |date=June 17, 2005 |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |publisher=[[Lee Enterprises]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708210252/http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date%3AD&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id%3D%28%2010ACE00E325E3ECB%20%29&p_docid=10ACE00E325E3ECB&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10ACE00E325E3ECB&f_openurl=yes&p |archivedate=July 8, 2019 |page=E8 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Diana Dawson, writing for ''[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]'', considered it an \"inspiring show for fun-loving tweens\".<ref name=\"shj\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Xc4oAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VNAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3981,1964897&dq=jessica+dicicco+buzz+on+maggie&hl=en|title=Maggie buzzes through life in new series|date=June 26, 2005|work=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]|publisher=Halifax Media Group|last=Dawson|first=Diana|page=50|volume=160|number=177|accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref> Kevin McDonough of ''[[Lawrence Journal-World]]'' wrote that ''The Buzz on Maggie'' \"strikes a decent balance between cartoon anarchy and Disney's you-go-girl sermonizing.\"<ref name=\"ljw\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uhlUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uzkNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5714,5537045&dq=jessica+dicicco+buzz+on+maggie&hl=en|title=Disney bugs out with ''Buzz''|work=[[Lawrence Journal-World]]|publisher=The World Company|date=June 17, 2005|last=McDonough|first=Kevin|accessdate=March 29, 2012|page=22|volume=147|number=168}}</ref> He praised the title character's \"bugged-out status\", writing that it prevents the stories from being \"too cute\".<ref name=\"ljw\"/> Jeanne Spreier of ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' graded ''The Buzz on Maggie'' with a B and regarded it as \"perfect cartooning\" for children. She wrote, \"[The show's] relatively simple plots, with equally simple resolutions and very clean dialogue, create fine cartoons for a schoolkid's late-afternoon respite.\"<ref name=\"dmn\">{{cite news |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%2010B4956350FC05C0%20)&p_docid=10B4956350FC05C0&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10B4956350FC05C0&f_openurl=yes&p |title=Cats with schemes; flies that teem in store for the kiddos this week |date=July 10, 2005 |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |last=Spreier |first=Jeanne |publisher=[[A. H. Belo Corporation]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708210409/http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date%3AD&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id%3D%28%2010B4956350FC05C0%20%29&p_docid=10B4956350FC05C0&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=10B4956350FC05C0&f_openurl=yes&p |archivedate=July 8, 2019 |page=2 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Similarly, the show's theme song \"Just the Way I Am\" received positive reactions; Hiltbrand called it \"great\",<ref name=\"tpi\"/> and Dawson wrote that \"every episode explodes with the dynamic theme song\".<ref name=\"shj\"/>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nIn 2005, Jorge Gutierrez was nominated for the Best Character Design in an Animated Television Production award at the [[33rd Annie Awards]], for his work in the episode \"Bella Con Carny\".<ref name=\"annie\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/33rdwinners.html |title=Legacy: 33rd Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (2005) |publisher=[[Annie Award]]s |year=2005 |accessdate=March 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517061205/http://annieawards.org/33rdwinners.html |archivedate=May 17, 2008 }}</ref> However, he lost to Ernie Gilbert from ''[[The Fairly OddParents]]''.<ref name=\"annie\"/> The next year, Bob Thiele Jr. and Dillon O'Brian received a nomination for Outstanding Original Song for the theme song \"Just the Way I Am\" at the [[33rd Daytime Emmy Awards]], but lost to the song \"Sunshine\" from ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmyonline.tv/emmy/33rdAnnual_daytime_nominees_only.html|title=33rd Annual Daytime Emmy Nominees|publisher=[[Emmy Award]]s|date=2006|accessdate=March 29, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306055845/http://www.emmyonline.tv/emmy/33rdAnnual_daytime_nominees_only.html|archivedate=March 6, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"emmy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmyonline.org/mediacenter/daytime_33rd_creative_win_data.html|title=The 33rd Annual Creative Craft Daytime Emmy Awards|publisher=Emmy Awards|date=2006|accessdate=March 29, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714125404/http://www.emmyonline.org/mediacenter/daytime_33rd_creative_win_data.html|archivedate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Result\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| [[33rd Annie Awards]]\n| Best Character Design in an Animated Television Production\n| {{unbulleted list|[[Jorge Gutierrez (animator)|Jorge Gutierrez]]|{{small|(for \"Bella Con Carny\")}}}}\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=\"annie\"/>\n|-\n| [[33rd Daytime Emmy Awards]]\n| Outstanding Original Song\n| {{unbulleted list|[[Bob Thiele, Jr.]]|Dillon O'Brian|{{small|(for \"Just the Way I Am\")}}}}\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=\"emmy\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|450208}}\n* {{bcdb |Walt_Disney_Studios/Television/The_Buzz_on_Maggie/ |The Buzz on Maggie}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-buzz-on-maggie}}\n\n{{Former Disney Channel original series}}\n{{ABC Kids}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buzz on Maggie, The}}\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American school television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American teen sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2005 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2006 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:Disney Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about brothers]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about families]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about insects]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about sisters]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney Television Animation]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Buzz on Maggie\n| image                = The Buzz on Maggie.png\n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{unbulleted list|[[Comedy series|Comedy]]|[[Slapstick]]}}\n| runtime              = 22 minutes\n| creator              = [[Dave Polsky]]\n| executive_producer   = {{unbulleted list|Dave Polsky|Dave Wasson|Laura Perkins Brittain (co-executive)}}\n| theme_music_composer = {{unbulleted list|[[Bob Thiele Jr.]]|Dillon O'Brian}}\n| director             = [[Dave Wasson]]\n| voices               = {{unbulleted list|[[Jessica DiCicco]]|[[David Kaufman (actor)|David Kaufman]]|[[Thom Adcox-Hernandez|Thom Adcox]]|[[Cree Summer]]|[[Brian Doyle-Murray]]|[[Susan Tolsky]]}}\n| opentheme            = \"Just the Way I Am\" by [[Skye Sweetnam]]\n| composer             = [[Adam Berry]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| network              = [[Disney Channel]]\n| picture_format       = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[SDTV]])\n| company              = [[Disney Television Animation|Walt Disney Television Animation]]\n| distributor          = [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television|Buena Vista Television]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2005|6|17}} \n| last_aired           = {{End date|2006|5|27}}\n| num_seasons          = 1 \n| num_episodes         = 21 (42 segments)\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n}}\n'''''The Buzz on Maggie''''' is an American [[cartoon series|animated television series]] created by [[Dave Polsky]] for [[Disney Channel]]. The series centers on an ambitious and expressive [[Preadolescence|tween]] [[fly]] named Maggie Pesky and her family and friends. The show is set in Stickyfeet, a city for insects located in a [[landfill|dump]]. While conceptualizing the series, Polsky wanted it to contain a playful aspect at adolescence and director [[Dave Wasson]] formed the overall look of the characters, being heavily influenced by early [[Walt Disney]] cartoon shorts. ''The Buzz on Maggie'' was Disney's first series to be fully animated in [[Adobe Flash]], a process done by [[Bardel Entertainment]] and [[Future Thought Productions]].\n\n''The Buzz on Maggie'' premiered on June 17, 2005, and aired its final episode on May 27, 2006, concluding its only season. The series received positive reviews from television critics, many of whom praised its humor, voice acting and writing. The theme song \u201cJust the Way I Am\u201d, performed by Canadian singer [[Skye Sweetnam]], was also met with critical praise and a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nomination in 2006. During its run, ''The Buzz on Maggie'' also received an [[Annie Award]] nomination for its character design.\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Maggie and Rayna.jpg|left|220px|The main characters, Maggie (left) and her best friend Rayna (right).|thumb]]\n''The Buzz on Maggie'' follows Maggie Pesky ([[Jessica DiCicco]]), an expressive 13-year-old fly and her family; parents Chauncey ([[Brian Doyle-Murray]]) and Frieda ([[Susan Tolsky]]);<ref>{{Cite episode| title = Faking History| series = The Buzz on Maggie| serieslink =| credits = Stein, Robin J; Grieb, Wendy; Wasson, Dave| network = [[Disney Channel]]| airdate = March 4, 2006| season = 1| number = 17a| time = 3:46 to 4:06| quote = '''Mrs. Pesky''': Oh hello, Mr. Bugspit! I'm Frieda. [...] '''Mr. Pesky''': Come in, Cornelius. I'm Chauncey Pesky.}}</ref> brothers Aldrin ([[David Kaufman (actor)|David Kaufman]]) and Pupert ([[Thom Adcox-Hernandez|Thom Adcox]]); and sister Bella ([[Tara Strong]]), who is still a [[maggot]]. The family resides in an old milk carton in a suburban fly metropolis called Stickyfeet, which is located in a [[landfill|dump]].<ref name=\"awn\"/><ref name=\"dmn\"/> Maggie has an ambitious and adventurous personality and aspires to become a rock star.<ref name=\"dmn\"/> Her approach to life often suffers unexpected consequences that puts herself in jeopardy, as she often follows her own impulses although they go against the rules or her parents' wishes.<ref name=\"shj\"/><ref name=\"tpi\"/> However, she ultimately learns her lesson,<ref name=\"shj\"/> which was one of the core themes for the show's conception.<ref name=\"awn\"/>\n\nMaggie attends a [[middle school|junior high school]] called Buzzdale Academy with her best friend Rayna Cartflight ([[Cree Summer]]) and [[archenemy|nemesis]] Dawn Swatworthy (Tara Strong). The school's staff include the sneaky Principal Peststrip ([[Jeff Bennett]]), pompous Mr. Bugspit ([[Curtis Armstrong]]) and gruff Mrs. Wingston ([[Candi Milo]]).<ref name=\"awn\"/> ''The Buzz on Maggie'' uses a [[slapstick]] comedy style and relies slightly on [[gross-out humor]].<ref name=\"ljw\"/> It also includes several insect aspects, such as flies' appetite for spoiled and rotten food.<ref name=\"ljw\"/><ref name=\"tpi\"/> The show features various references to [[popular culture|pop culture]] and common themes, such as sibling rivalry and [[peer pressure]], from a fly's point of view.<ref name=\"tpi\"/>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:JessicaDiCicco.jpg|thumb|upright|Newcomer [[Jessica DiCicco]] provided the voice of Maggie.]]\nThe concept of ''The Buzz on Maggie'' was created by [[Dave Polsky]], a former writer on ''[[Scary Movie 2]]'' and ''[[South Park]]''.<ref name=\"anmag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/maggie-begins-buzzing-on-disney/ |title=Maggie Begins Buzzing on Disney |work=[[Animation Magazine]] |date=June 17, 2005 |last=Zahed |first=Ramin |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119010723/http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/maggie-begins-buzzing-on-disney/ |archivedate=November 19, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In an early interview for [[Animation World Network]], he explained that the series utilizes a playful aspect at adolescence, naming it \"individuality vs. conformity\".<ref name=\"awn\"/> He said, \"Maggie must learn how to pursue her agenda without alienating those she cares about. More often than not, Maggie learns that it is difficult to negotiate life on her terms without burning bridges.\"<ref name=\"awn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/news/television/disneys-buzz-maggie-flies-debutes-disney-channel |title=Disney's ''The Buzz on Maggie'' Flies Debutes on Disney Channel |last=Baisley |first=Sarah |date=June 17, 2005 |work=[[Animation World Network]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140417095950/http://www.awn.com/news/television/disneys-buzz-maggie-flies-debutes-disney-channel |archivedate=April 17, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Dave Wasson]], the creator of the animated series ''[[Time Squad]]'', served as the director, and executively produced the series with Polsky, while Laura Perkins Brittain was the co-executive producer.<ref name=\"awn\"/>\n\nWasson formed Maggie's character design and supported the use of [[Adobe Flash]] for animating the series. He told ''[[Animation Magazine]]'' that he was convinced Flash was a \"good way to go\" as he had had previous experience with the program, such as commercials and short films.<ref name=\"anmag\"/> The series became Disney's first to be fully animated in Flash.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/852665411.html?dids=852665411:852665411&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+12%2C+2005&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=ON+THIS+WEEK%3A+JUNE+12-18&pqatl=google|title=On this Week: June 12\u201318|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|date=June 12, 2005|accessdate=March 29, 2012|page=Y.03}}</ref> Following the cancellation of [[Kids' WB]]'s ''[[\u00a1Mucha Lucha!]]'', many animators from that series were hired to work on ''The Buzz on Maggie''.<ref name=\"anmag\"/> For the character designs, Wasson was heavily influenced by early cartoon shorts by [[Tex Avery]], [[Warner Bros.]] and [[Walt Disney]]. He noted that the characters in ''The Buzz on Maggie'' have \"a lot of 1930s touches\" and wear white gloves, which is a direct homage to the cartoon shorts.<ref name=\"anmag\"/> The characters also have [[anime]]-inspired designs with oversized heads and large eyes.<ref name=\"am\"/> Wasson stated that the concept of Maggie living in a dump gave him a \"lot of visual opportunities\".<ref name=\"anmag\"/> [[Jorge Gutierrez (animator)|Jorge Gutierrez]] supervised the character design and Roman Laney supervised location and prop design in addition to background paint. The animation was done by [[Bardel Entertainment]] and [[Future Thought Productions]].<ref name=\"awn\"/><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/futurethoughtanimation/thatdarnjesus/prweb558627.htm|title=Future Thought Flashes onto the Big Screen at MIPCOM|date=October 5, 2007|location=San Jose, California|publisher=[[PR Web]]|accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe series' theme song \"Just the Way I Am\" was composed by [[Bob Thiele Jr.]] and Dillon O'Brian, and performed by Canadian singer [[Skye Sweetnam]].<ref name=\"awn\"/> The song is about pride, acceptance and empowerment.<ref name=\"ljw\"/> [[Adam Berry]] did the show's [[film score|score]].<ref name=\"awn\"/> [[Charlie Adler]] voice directed ''The Buzz on Maggie'' and helmed [[voice casting]] with Jamie Thomason.<ref name=\"awn\"/> Newcomer [[Jessica DiCicco]] was cast as Maggie,<ref name=\"tpi\"/> her first main role on a television series, preceding her role on ''[[Loonatics Unleashed]]'', which premiered the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/loonatics-cast-unleashed/|title=''Loonatics'' Cast Unleashed|work=Animation Magazine|last=Ball|first=Ryan|date=June 6, 2005|accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref> The rest of the main cast included [[David Kaufman (actor)|David Kaufman]], [[Thom Adcox]], [[Cree Summer]], [[Brian Doyle-Murray]] and [[Susan Tolsky]].<ref name=\"awn\"/> [[Tara Strong]] voiced Maggie's nemesis Dawn, among other minor characters.<ref name=\"awn\"/> The series had a few guest voice actors, such as [[Laraine Newman]], [[Paul Rodriguez (actor) |Paul Rodriguez]], and [[Jon Polito]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/71769-Ladybugged.html|title=Ladybugged (2005)|publisher=[[Big Cartoon Database]]|accessdate=July 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/77553-Those_Pesky_Roaches.html|title=Those Pesky Roaches (2005)|publisher=Big Cartoon Database|accessdate=July 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''The Buzz on Maggie'' premiered on Disney Channel on Friday June 17, 2005, At 8:00PM And 8:30PM with two back-to-back episodes.<ref name=\"slpd\"/><ref name=\"anmag\"/> The next week, it moved to its regular timeslot in the channel's weekend block.<ref name=\"tpi\"/><ref name=\"anmag\"/> Each half-hour episode consists of two different segments.<ref name=\"dmn\"/> ''The Buzz on Maggie'' aired for one season, comprising 21 half-hour episodes. The final episode, containing the segments \"Synchronized Flying\" and \"Roach Hotel\", aired on May 27, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/detail/tv-show.aspx?tvobjectid=194683&more=ucepisodelist&episodeid=5567075|title=Episode Detail: Synchronized Flying; Roach Hotel&nbsp;\u2013 ''The Buzz on Maggie''|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 2005, ''The Buzz on Maggie'' was picked up by sister network [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref name=\"am\"/> The network began airing reruns of the show from September 17, 2005, to January 21, 2006 on the Saturday morning block [[ABC Kids (United States)|ABC Kids]].<ref name=\"ABCKids\">{{cite press release|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=090705_11|title=ABC Kids premieres new fall season Saturday, September 17, on the ABC Television Network|publisher=ABC Medianet|date=September 7, 2005|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> According to [[Nielsen Media Research]], the ABC premiere acquired a 1.6 rating in the Kids 2\u201311 demographic, and a 1.4 rating in Tweens 9\u201314, as well as a 7% share in both demographics.<ref name=\"abcrating\"/> The premiere was that timeslot's highest-rated broadcast in nearly three months across the block's three key demographics, Kids 2\u201311, Kids 6\u201311 and Tweens 9\u201314.<ref name=\"abcrating\">{{cite press release|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=092205_06|title=Ratings Report for ABC Kids For Saturday September 17, 2005|publisher=ABC Medianet|accessdate=March 31, 2012|date=September 22, 2005}}</ref> During the ABC Kids broadcasts, the series carried an [[E/I]] designation.<ref name=\"ABCKids\"/>\n\n==Episodes==\nAll episodes were directed by [[Dave Wasson]].\n{{Episode table|background=1254A4|overall=|title=|writer=|airdate=|prodcode=|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = The Flyinator\"<hr>\"Ladybugged \n| WrittenBy       = Rachel Duguay<hr>Alicia Sky Varinaitis\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|6|17}}\n| ProdCode        = 103\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''The Flyinator'''\": When Maggie can't see the same movies as Aldrin she starts trying to be better than he is; she sneaks into an R-rated movie to be better than he is.<hr>\"'''Ladybugged'''\": When Maggie thinks up a theme for the school dance, it is quickly threatened by a new student, who apparently has a better theme.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| Title           = Funball\"<hr>\"The Science Whatchamacallit\n| WrittenBy       = Dan Fybel and Rich Rinaldi<hr>Rachel Duguay\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|6|17}}\n| ProdCode        = 102\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Funball'''\": Maggie devises a new game for her little brother Pupert to play so he can beat Aldrin at something, but when Aldrin starts to get the hang of the game things take an unexpected turn for the worse.<hr>\"'''The Science Whatchamacallit'''\": Maggie and Rayna try to get their science partners who are really smart to do all the work for an assignment, but when it comes time to present the projects something unexpected happens.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| Title           = The Candidate\"<hr>\"Germy\n| WrittenBy       = Rachelle Romberg<hr>[[Dave Polsky]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|6|24}}\n| ProdCode        = 101\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''The Candidate'''\": The school bully faces some competition for the title of Homecoming Queen when Maggie gives an ugly butterfly named Maria a makeover.<hr>\"'''Germy'''\": When Maggie wants to bring home a pet germ, her dad won't let her so she sneaks it home, but faces a problem with training especially when Maggie's parents find out. \n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| Title           = Lunch Lady\"<hr>\"Love Stinks\n| WrittenBy       = Dan Fybel and Rich Rinaldi<hr>Laura Perkins Brittain\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2005|7|1}}\n| ProdCode        = 104\n| ShortSummary    = \"'''Lunch Lady'''\": Maggie accidentally gets the lunch lady to quit, causing the parents to take over the school.<hr>\"'''Love Stinks'''\": Maggie goes on a date with a stinkbug even though she doesn't want to.\n| LineColor       = 1254A4\n}}\n{{Episo