[Ben Gordon (footballer, born 1991)|Ben Gordon]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]]\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Chris Lewington, Ben Gordon and Sean Clohessy join Colchester Utd|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28114781|publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 July 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|3 July 2014\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Alex Cooper (footballer)|Alex Cooper]]\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Falkirk: Jamie MacDonald one of five new arrivals|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28147322|publisher=BBC Sport|date=3 July 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|11 July 2014\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Gary Glen]]\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]]\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Livingston bring in Glen|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/livingston-bring-in-glen/|publisher=SPFL|date=11 July 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|22 July 2014\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Evangelos Ikonomou]]\n|{{flagicon|CYP}} [[Doxa Katokopias F.C.|Doxa Katokopias]]\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross County: Evangelos Oikonomou makes second exit|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27477575|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 July 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|15 August 2014\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Stuart Kettlewell]]\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Brora Rangers F.C.|Brora Rangers]]\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross County: Midfielder Stuart Kettlewell leaves club|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28806942|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 August 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|13 October 2014\n|{{flagicon|NED}} [[Marc Klok]]\n|{{flagicon|BUL}} [[PFC Cherno More Varna|Cherno More Varna]]\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Early Ross County release for Marc Klok|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28856038|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 October 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|28 October 2014\n|{{flagicon|NED}} [[Melvin de Leeuw]]\n|Released\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross County: Melvin De Leeuw exits 'for personal reasons'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29813165|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 October 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|7 November 2014\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} Rosario Latouchent\n|Released\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Rosario Latouchent leaves Ross County|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/sport/football/ross-county/394394/undefined-headline-636/|publisher=pressandjournal|date=7 November 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|13 November 2014\n|{{flagicon|SLO}} [[Uro\u0161 Celcer]]\n|Released\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross County: Jim McIntyre targets signings as three exit|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30037721|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|13 November 2014\n|{{flagicon|BEL}} [[Tim Dreesen]]\n|Released\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross County: Jim McIntyre targets signings as three exit|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30037721|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|12 January 2015\n|{{flagicon|NED}} [[Jordi Balk]]\n|{{flagicon|NED}} [[FC Oss]]\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross County: Jim McIntyre targets signings as three exit|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30037721|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Balk maakt seizoen af bij FC Oss (in Dutch) |url=http://oss.kliknieuws.nl/forum/discussie/90790 |publisher=kliknieuws |date=12 January 2015 |accessdate=11 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113135351/http://oss.kliknieuws.nl/forum/discussie/90790 |archivedate=13 January 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|2 February 2015\n|{{flagicon|NED}} [[Darren Maatsen]]\n|{{flagicon|NED}} [[FC Den Bosch|Den Bosch]]\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross County: Darren Maatsen leaves for Den Bosch|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31108733|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2015|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|2 February 2015\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Lewis Toshney]]\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]]\n|Free<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross County: Darren Maatsen leaves for Den Bosch|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31108733|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2015|accessdate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Ross County F.C. seasons]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n{{Ross County F.C.}}\n{{2014\u201315 in Scottish football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014-15 Ross County F.C. Season}}\n[[Category:Scottish football clubs 2014\u201315 season|Ross County]]\n[[Category:Ross County F.C. seasons]]\n", "name_user": "Aidan Lynn 1998", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014%E2%80%9315_Ross_County_F.C._season"}
{"title_page": "Tom Meade", "text_new": "'''Thomas \"Tom\" Meade''' (19{{Nbsp}}January 1939{{Spaced en dash}}August 2013) was an American automobile designer and dealer best known for his ''Thomassima'' series of [[custom cars]] based on [[Ferrari]] engines and chassis.\n\n== Early life ==\nTom Meade was born in [[Hollywood]] on 19 January 1939, to a [[single mother]]. He spent his youth with her in [[Australia]] and [[Honolulu, Hawaii]]. When he reached the high school age, they moved in [[Newport Beach, California]]. He graduated at 17 and enrolled in the [[U.S. Navy]] where he was trained as an [[Avionics|avionic]] engineer, until his leave in 1960.<ref name=mom>{{cite web |url=http://www.thomassima.com/ |title=Meade of Modena. An American Dreamer In the Land of Artful Science|last=Crane |first=Larry |date= |website=thomassima.com |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne day, during his walk home from work in [[Costa Mesa]], he spotted through the open door of a garage the back of a 1957 [[Ferrari 500 TRC]], calling it the most beautiful car he had ever seen. The owner initially tried to sell the car to Meade for a disproportionate amount with no avail; then he revealed to have bought the car in [[Rome, Italy]], where there was a warehouse full of old [[Sports car racing|racecars]] for sale at a low price.<ref name=mom/><ref name=rt>{{cite magazine |last=Coltrin |first=Pete |orig-year=December 1970|date=7 November 2014|title=Tom Meade's wild Ferrari Thomassima was the P4/5 of its day |url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/a6441/ferrari-thomassima/ |magazine=[[Road & Track]] |location=New York |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines]]}}</ref><ref name=oct>{{cite magazine |last=Sonnery |first=Marc |date=March 2020 |title=Maximum Dose |url= |magazine=[[Octane (magazine)|Octane]] |location=Wollaston, Northamptonshire |publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|pp=86\u201397}}</ref>{{rp|89}}<br/>\nFascinated, Meade decided on impulse that he would put his hands on one of those cars at any cost. In the autumn of 1960, he left home with only $50 and hitchhiked to [[New Orleans]] where he signed on to a freighter heading for [[Stavanger]], Norway, as [[steward's assistant]]. Once he arrived, he crossed Europe and made his way to Italy.<ref name=mom/><ref name=rt/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|89}}\n\n== Life in Italy ==\nOnce in Rome, Meade found a job as an [[extra (acting)|extra]] in [[Dino De Laurentiis]]\u2019 1961 film ''[[The Best of Enemies (1961 film)|The Best of Enemies]]'': he played a background English officer at night, and fruitlessly searched for the fabled warehouse during the day. In the end, he realized that the warehouse was only a myth and thus left Rome for [[Modena]], where the headquarters of Ferrari and [[Maserati]] were located.<ref name=mom/>\n\nMeade had no contacts in Modena and no money for lodging, sleeping outdoors when he first arrived. Shortly after his arrival, he visited the Maserati factory during the evening, after operations closed for the day. By chance, [[Aurelio Bertocchi]], the son of Maserati race director [[Guerino Bertocchi]], was working late and gave Meade a factory tour, thinking Meade was a potential customer for a new [[Maserati 3500 GT]]. During the tour, Meade spotted a retired racing car in storage at the factory, a [[Maserati 350S]], chassis 3503. Meade made a deal with Bertocchi to purchase the car for $420. It was missing an engine and needed body repairs. Through Bertocchi, Meade made contact with the shops of [[Neri and Bonacini]] and [[Medardo Fantuzzi]], in order to find repair facilities. Meade met [[Lloyd Casner|Lloyd \"Lucky\" Casner]] of the [[Camoradi]] racing team while visiting the Maserati factory, and was subsequently able to purchase a [[Chevy small block|Chevy V8]] engine from him. This engine originated from a [[Zora Arkus-Duntov|Arkus-Duntov]] engineered racing [[Chevrolet Corvette|Corvette]] that was wrecked by Camoradi team mechanic [[Bob Wallace (test_driver)|Bob Wallace]]. Meade and his collaborators rebuilt the 350S with the Chevy engine and customized the body with a removable hard top. Meade shipped the car to [[San Francisco]] in 1962, where it was subsequently crashed by an associate and sold for  $2700.<ref name=\"mom\" /><ref name=\"ait\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://magazine.ferrari.com/blog/2014/08/italian-heart-american-blood/|title=ITALIAN HEART, AMERICAN BLOOD|last=Barlow|first=Jason|date=15 August 2014|website=The Official Ferrari Magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831103306/https://magazine.ferrari.com/blog/2014/08/italian-heart-american-blood/|archive-date=31 August 2014|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"rt\" />\n\nThis first project allowed Meade to establish a network of contacts in Modena that would allow his future projects of rebuilding, customizing and dealing cars. In addition to Bertocchi, Neri, Bonacini and Fantuzzi, Meade's contacts included [[Piero Drogo]], [[David Piper (racing driver)|David Piper]], [[Alejandro de Tomaso]], [[Giovanni Volpi|Count Giovanni Volpi]], ''[[Road & Track]]'' journalist Peter Coltrin and [[Carroll Shelby]]. Meade took up residence in the Carrozzeria Fantuzzi workshop and took instruction in hand-forming and repairing bodywork from Medardo Fantuzzi. He briefly left Italy in 1962, returning in 1963 whereupon he began renting an apartment and garage adjacent to the [[Autodromo di Modena]]. Soon after, Meade began buying and selling a higher volume of cars, including many which were exported to the United States. These included another Maserati 350S, a [[Maserati Tipo 61|Maserati Tipo 63]], [[Ferrari 250 GTO]]<nowiki/>s, a [[Ferrari 330 P3|330 P3]], a [[Ferrari 250 LM|250 LM]], a [[Ferrari 250 GT SWB|250 GT SWB]], [[Ferrari 250 GT Lusso|250 GT Lusso]]<nowiki/>s and others. Meade's customers included Richard Merritt (founder of the [[Ferrari Club of America]]) and Los Angeles-based Ferrari importer Edwin K. Niles. During this period from 1963 to approximately 1970, Meade constructed his ''Thomassima'' series and several other projects based on various chassis and engines. At one point during this time, Meade shared a storage space with David Piper's racing team. By 1970, Meade established a business in Modena under the name \"Tom Meade's Used Sports Car Center of Italy,\" where in addition to buying, selling, rebuilding and customizing used cars, he sold and manufactured spare parts and accessories with an emphasis on selling to overseas customers.<ref name=\"ait\" /><ref name=\"mom\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"rt\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDuring the early 1970s, multiple circumstances coincided to end Meade's business in Modena. Due to the [[1973 oil crisis]] demand for sports cars was lower, while increasing safety regulations, speed limits and changing public opinion further limited the market for Meade's cars. Meade also claimed that his Modenese collaborators were discouraged from working with him, as established interests in the region believed he was getting too much publicity. Meade left Modena and briefly opened a restoration shop in [[Milan]], where he became friends with former Ferrari engineer [[Carlo Chiti]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=oct/>{{rp|92\u20134}}\n\nMeade left Italy at some point during the 1970s, storing the cars and parts he had accumulated for his business in a warehouse near [[Lake Como]].<ref name=\"mom\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Thomassima series ==\nThe first full-body, Meade-made car was based on a [[Ferrari 250 GT]] and finished in 1964.<ref name=rt/> Meade made the car more aggressive with a longer and lower snout, gill-like vents behind all wheels, and a roof consisting in a straight line sloping from the windshield to the car tail. This car was destroyed in the [[1966 flood of the Arno]] in [[Florence]] where it was attending an exhibition.<ref name=rt/><ref name=tac>{{cite web |url=https://www.theautochannel.com/publications/magazines/sci/aug-sept-98/pg78.frame |title=Meade'n Voyage|last= |first= |date= |website=[[The Auto Channel]] |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} Nevertheless, it was influential on later Meade cars, with a source retroactively \u2013 and unofficially \u2013 calling it the ''Thomassima Zero''.<ref name=oct/><ref name=\":1\" />{{rp|91}}{{efn|Some sources incorrectly calls this car the actual Thomassima I, making it the car which was lost in Florence<ref name=mom/>}}\n\nThe ''Thomassima I'' was made under the request of a unknown Swiss baron who sought a replacement for his [[Corvette C2|Corvette]] in order to remain competitive against the [[Shelby Cobra]]s.<ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} Meade based this \"anti-Cobra\" on a Ferrari 250 GT chassis fitted with a powerful Chevrolet V8 engine in its front,<ref name=rt/><ref name=mom/> and covered with a heavily altered bodywork which included [[Gull-wing door|gullwings]] that could have been removed and put into the car trunk, an idea which Meade considered unprecedented at the time.<ref name=mom/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}}\n\n[[File:1967 Ferrari 330 P3slash4, Glickenhaus (Lime Rock).jpg|thumb|The Ferrari 330 P3/P4. Meade's Thomassima II was his idea of how this Ferrari should have looked like]]\nThe ''Thomassima II''{{efn|Some older sources incorrectly calls this car the first Thomassima built.<ref name=rt/><ref name=ait>{{cite web |url=https://mycarquest.com/2016/05/tom-meade-americano-italia.html |title=Tom Meade: An Americano In Italia \u2013 Doing What All Of Us Wished We Could Do\u2026|last=Wyss |first=Wallace |date=1 May 2016 |website=mycarquest.com |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>}} was requested in late 1966 by Harry Windsor from [[Los Gatos, California]]. Windsor wanted a [[mid-engine car]] resembling the Ferrari 330 P3 or [[Ferrari 330 P4|P4]].<ref name=rt/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} Meade then proceeded to create his idea of how the P3/P4 should have looked like, but it proved very challenging.<ref name=oct/><br/>\nHe had to radically modify the frame of a [[Cooper T43]] [[Formula One]] car, and fitting it with a Ferrari 250 GT [[Ferrari Colombo engine|Colombo V12 engine]] coupled to a 4-speed [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] [[gearbox]].<ref name=rt/><ref name=ait/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}}<ref name=mom/> For the bodywork, Meade was greatly helped by [[Piero Drogo]] of [[Carrozzeria Sports Cars]]. The final result was ready in the 1967, and was a little longer and more muscular car than a P4, weighing less than {{convert|2000|lb|kg}} and sporting {{convert|240|hp|kW}}, with a [[Convertible#Detachable hardtop|detachable hardtop]].<ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}}<ref name=mom/> The Thomassima II was shipped to California where Windsor rebranded it as a \"Ferrari 250 P/4 Roadster\" and exhibited it at the 1968 [[Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance]] where it won a class award.<ref name=mom/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} Despite the fact that it was improperly called a Ferrari, the Thomassima II made Meade a well known figure in his field.<ref name=mom/> In 1971 the car made a cameo appearance in [[George Lucas]]\u2019 directorial debut film ''[[THX 1138]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Breeze |first=Joe |date=5 January 2015|title=The police drove Lola T70s in George Lucas\u2019s directorial debut |url=https://www.classicdriver.com/en/article/cars/police-drove-lola-t70s-george-lucass-directorial-debut |magazine=Classic Driver |location= |publisher=}}</ref> In later times the car was crashed, then purchased in the early 1980s by Larry Hatfield and later restored. It starred at the 2015 [[Monterey Car Week#Concorso Italiano|Concorso Italiano at Monterey]].<ref name=mom/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} As of December 2016, the car is still in Hatfield's possession.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Stone |first=Matt |date=8 December 2016|title=Mimicking Maranello |url=https://www.forza-mag.com/issues/155/articles/mimicking-maranello |magazine=Forza |issue=155 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Thomassima III'' was built not before the 1968, and its completion required over a year of work.<ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}}<ref name=rt/> The donor car was a 1958 [[Ferrari 250#250 GT Coup\u00e9 Pinin Farina|Ferrari 250 GT Pininfarina Coup\u00e9]] (chassis number 1065GT) powered by a [[Ferrari Colombo engine#250|3L V12 engine]]. The gearbox was replaced with a 5-speed ZF and the brakes were upgraded.<ref name=rt/><ref name=ait/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} The bodywork was altered dramatically, even further than the earlier \"Thomassima Zero\", resulting in an extremely low, muscular, front-engined coupe featuring gullwings, twisted exhausts on both sides and [[centerlock wheel]]s. Interiors were lavish, with a steel-casted steering wheel. Meade claimed to have put a particular emphasis into the finish.<ref name=rt/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91\u20132}}<ref name=mom/> The Thomassima III was the car that brought Meade the most fame, and he often used it for promoting himself. He considered it his masterpiece and decided not to sell it to anyone.<ref name=rt/><ref name=mom/> In December 1970 it was featured on ''Road & Track'', appeared on Italian TV, ''[[60 Minutes]]''<ref name=60min>{{Cite episode |title=Tom Meade |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jazEBNIV7K8 |access-date=19 April 2020 |series=60 Minutes |series-link= |first=Winston |last=Burdett |network=CBS |date=1970}}</ref> and on [[Walter Cronkite]]'s talk show, won awards in car shows in Italy and USA, and became a [[Hot Wheels]] scale model.<ref name=rt/><ref name=ait/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|92}} Prior to Meade's departure from Italy, the Thomassima III was placed in long-term storage in a facility near Lake Como, Italy.<ref name=\"mom\" /> It was exhibited at the [[Museo Ferrari]] in Maranello during 2014, as part of the \"California Dreaming\" exhibition.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.velocetoday.com/california-dreaming-at-the-ferrari-museum/|title=California Dreaming at the Ferrari Museum|last=Sharp|first=Jonathan|date=25 November 2014|website=www.velocetoday.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> As of March 2020, the Thomassima III is owned by Meade's son and still kept in Italy.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=oct/>{{rp|94}}\n\n== Other projects ==\n\n[[File:1963 Ferrari 250 GT Lusso Fantuzzi (19630529192).jpg|alt=Ferrari 250 GT Lusso with modified bodywork by Fantuzzi and Meade|thumb|Ferrari 250 GT Lusso (chassis 4383GT) with modified bodywork by Fantuzzi and Meade]]\nIn addition to the ''Thomassima'' cars, Meade constructed multiple other custom cars with the help of his Italian collaborators. These included the [[Neri and Bonacini#Ferrari Nembo|Nembo series]] of Ferrari 250 GT-based road cars, built in collaboration with Neri and Bonacini. Three Nembo spiders and one Nembo coupe were built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/lotfinder/lot/1960-ferrari-250-gt-nembo-spyder-4554166-details.aspx|title=1960 FERRARI 250 GT 'NEMBO SPYDER'|website=www.christies.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Sonnery|first=Marc|date=1998-04-25|title=The Nembo Ferraris - Part I|url=|journal=Ferrari Market Letter|volume=23|issue=9|pages=1\u20135|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=Jonathan|date=November 1966|title=Neri and Bonacini|url=|journal=Road & Track|volume=18|issue=3|pages=42\u201344|via=}}</ref>\n\nMeade modified 7 or 8 [[Ferrari 250 GT Lusso]]<nowiki/>s with [[Ferrari 330 LMB|330 LMB]]-style front bodywork, including triple \"nostril\"-style air intakes and/or aerodynamic covered headlights. These cars were mostly purchased in wrecked or non-working condition from the [[Emilia-Romagna|Emilia-Romagna region]] near Modena, rebuilt and modified then resold.<ref name=\"mom\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journal.classiccars.com/2017/12/16/meade-modena-cars-sculptures-personal-expression/|title=Meade of Modena: Cars as sculptures of personal expression|last=Crane|first=Larry|date=2017-12-17|website=ClassicCars.com Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fantasyjunction.com/sold/1963-ferrari-250gt-lusso-speciale-by-fantuzzi/overview|title=1963 Ferrari 250GT Lusso Speciale by Fantuzzi|last=|first=|date=|website=www.fantasyjunction.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barchetta.cc/english/All.Ferraris/Detail/4587GT.250.GTL.htm|title=250 GT Lusso s/n 4587GT|website=www.barchetta.cc|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barchetta.cc/english/All.Ferraris/Detail/4383GT.250.GTL.htm|title=250 GT Lusso s/n 4383GT|website=www.barchetta.cc|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><br />\n\n== Later life ==\nAfter leaving Italy sometime during the 1970s, Meade spent approximately two decades traveling in Asia. In 1993, Meade returned to Los Angeles in order to take care of his mother. He began planning the construction of a ''Thomassima IV'' (sometimes styled ''Thomassima IIII''), which was to have a [[Carbon fiber reinforced polymer|carbon fiber]] body and a [[Ferrari 333 SP]] engine.<ref name=\"mom\" /><ref name=\"ait\" />\n\nMeade died in August 2013.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://drive-my.com/en/retro-carss/item/4096-1969-thomassima-iii.html|title=1969 Thomassima III|last=Sonnery|first=Marc|date=31 January 2020|website=Drive|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nMeade had an adopted son, who maintains his estate and works in the luxury goods industry.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><br />\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meade, Tom}}\n[[Category:Ferrari people]]\n[[Category:Maserati people]]\n[[Category:Coachbuilders of Italy]]\n[[Category:Vehicle modification people]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Draft article|name=Tom Meade}}\n'''Thomas \"Tom\" Meade''' (19{{Nbsp}}January 1939{{Spaced en dash}}August 2013) was an American automobile designer and dealer best known for his ''Thomassima'' series of [[custom cars]] based on [[Ferrari]] engines and chassis.\n\n== Early life ==\nTom Meade was born in [[Hollywood]] on 19 January 1939, to a [[single mother]]. He spent his youth with her in [[Australia]] and [[Honolulu, Hawaii]]. When he reached the high school age, they moved in [[Newport Beach, California]]. He graduated at 17 and enrolled in the [[U.S. Navy]] where he was trained as an [[Avionics|avionic]] engineer, until his leave in 1960.<ref name=mom>{{cite web |url=http://www.thomassima.com/ |title=Meade of Modena. An American Dreamer In the Land of Artful Science|last=Crane |first=Larry |date= |website=thomassima.com |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne day, during his walk home from work in [[Costa Mesa]], he spotted through the open door of a garage the back of a 1957 [[Ferrari 500 TRC]], calling it the most beautiful car he had ever seen. The owner initially tried to sell the car to Meade for a disproportionate amount with no avail; then he revealed to have bought the car in [[Rome, Italy]], where there was a warehouse full of old [[Sports car racing|racecars]] for sale at a low price.<ref name=mom/><ref name=rt>{{cite magazine |last=Coltrin |first=Pete |orig-year=December 1970|date=7 November 2014|title=Tom Meade's wild Ferrari Thomassima was the P4/5 of its day |url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/a6441/ferrari-thomassima/ |magazine=[[Road & Track]] |location=New York |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines]]}}</ref><ref name=oct>{{cite magazine |last=Sonnery |first=Marc |date=March 2020 |title=Maximum Dose |url= |magazine=[[Octane (magazine)|Octane]] |location=Wollaston, Northamptonshire |publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|pp=86\u201397}}</ref>{{rp|89}}<br/>\nFascinated, Meade decided on impulse that he would put his hands on one of those cars at any cost. In the autumn of 1960, he left home with only $50 and hitchhiked to [[New Orleans]] where he signed on to a freighter heading for [[Stavanger]], Norway, as [[steward's assistant]]. Once he arrived, he crossed Europe and made his way to Italy.<ref name=mom/><ref name=rt/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|89}}\n\n== Life in Italy ==\nOnce in Rome, Meade found a job as an [[extra (acting)|extra]] in [[Dino De Laurentiis]]\u2019 1961 film ''[[The Best of Enemies (1961 film)|The Best of Enemies]]'': he played a background English officer at night, and fruitlessly searched for the fabled warehouse during the day. In the end, he realized that the warehouse was only a myth and thus left Rome for [[Modena]], where the headquarters of Ferrari and [[Maserati]] were located.<ref name=mom/>\n\nMeade had no contacts in Modena and no money for lodging, sleeping outdoors when he first arrived. Shortly after his arrival, he visited the Maserati factory during the evening, after operations closed for the day. By chance, [[Aurelio Bertocchi]], the son of Maserati race director [[Guerino Bertocchi]], was working late and gave Meade a factory tour, thinking Meade was a potential customer for a new [[Maserati 3500 GT]]. During the tour, Meade spotted a retired racing car in storage at the factory, a [[Maserati 350S]], chassis 3503. Meade made a deal with Bertocchi to purchase the car for $420. It was missing an engine and needed body repairs. Through Bertocchi, Meade made contact with the shops of [[Neri and Bonacini]] and [[Medardo Fantuzzi]], in order to find repair facilities. Meade met [[Lloyd Casner|Lloyd \"Lucky\" Casner]] of the [[Camoradi]] racing team while visiting the Maserati factory, and was subsequently able to purchase a [[Chevy small block|Chevy V8]] engine from him. This engine originated from a [[Zora Arkus-Duntov|Arkus-Duntov]] engineered racing [[Chevrolet Corvette|Corvette]] that was wrecked by Camoradi team mechanic [[Bob Wallace (test_driver)|Bob Wallace]]. Meade and his collaborators rebuilt the 350S with the Chevy engine and customized the body with a removable hard top. Meade shipped the car to [[San Francisco]] in 1962, where it was subsequently crashed by an associate and sold for  $2700.<ref name=\"mom\" /><ref name=\"ait\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://magazine.ferrari.com/blog/2014/08/italian-heart-american-blood/|title=ITALIAN HEART, AMERICAN BLOOD|last=Barlow|first=Jason|date=15 August 2014|website=The Official Ferrari Magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831103306/https://magazine.ferrari.com/blog/2014/08/italian-heart-american-blood/|archive-date=31 August 2014|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"rt\" />\n\nThis first project allowed Meade to establish a network of contacts in Modena that would allow his future projects of rebuilding, customizing and dealing cars. In addition to Bertocchi, Neri, Bonacini and Fantuzzi, Meade's contacts included [[Piero Drogo]], [[David Piper (racing driver)|David Piper]], [[Alejandro de Tomaso]], [[Giovanni Volpi|Count Giovanni Volpi]], ''[[Road & Track]]'' journalist Peter Coltrin and [[Carroll Shelby]]. Meade took up residence in the Carrozzeria Fantuzzi workshop and took instruction in hand-forming and repairing bodywork from Medardo Fantuzzi. He briefly left Italy in 1962, returning in 1963 whereupon he began renting an apartment and garage adjacent to the [[Autodromo di Modena]]. Soon after, Meade began buying and selling a higher volume of cars, including many which were exported to the United States. These included another Maserati 350S, a [[Maserati Tipo 61|Maserati Tipo 63]], [[Ferrari 250 GTO]]<nowiki/>s, a [[Ferrari 330 P3|330 P3]], a [[Ferrari 250 LM|250 LM]], a [[Ferrari 250 GT SWB|250 GT SWB]], [[Ferrari 250 GT Lusso|250 GT Lusso]]<nowiki/>s and others. Meade's customers included Richard Merritt (founder of the [[Ferrari Club of America]]) and Los Angeles-based Ferrari importer Edwin K. Niles. During this period from 1963 to approximately 1970, Meade constructed his ''Thomassima'' series and several other projects based on various chassis and engines. At one point during this time, Meade shared a storage space with David Piper's racing team. By 1970, Meade established a business in Modena under the name \"Tom Meade's Used Sports Car Center of Italy,\" where in addition to buying, selling, rebuilding and customizing used cars, he sold and manufactured spare parts and accessories with an emphasis on selling to overseas customers.<ref name=\"ait\" /><ref name=\"mom\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"rt\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDuring the early 1970s, multiple circumstances coincided to end Meade's business in Modena. Due to the [[1973 oil crisis]] demand for sports cars was lower, while increasing safety regulations, speed limits and changing public opinion further limited the market for Meade's cars. Meade also claimed that his Modenese collaborators were discouraged from working with him, as established interests in the region believed he was getting too much publicity. Meade left Modena and briefly opened a restoration shop in [[Milan]], where he became friends with former Ferrari engineer [[Carlo Chiti]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=oct/>{{rp|92\u20134}}\n\nMeade left Italy at some point during the 1970s, storing the cars and parts he had accumulated for his business in a warehouse near [[Lake Como]].<ref name=\"mom\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Thomassima series ==\nThe first full-body, Meade-made car was based on a [[Ferrari 250 GT]] and finished in 1964.<ref name=rt/> Meade made the car more aggressive with a longer and lower snout, gill-like vents behind all wheels, and a roof consisting in a straight line sloping from the windshield to the car tail. This car was destroyed in the [[1966 flood of the Arno]] in [[Florence]] where it was attending an exhibition.<ref name=rt/><ref name=tac>{{cite web |url=https://www.theautochannel.com/publications/magazines/sci/aug-sept-98/pg78.frame |title=Meade'n Voyage|last= |first= |date= |website=[[The Auto Channel]] |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} Nevertheless, it was influential on later Meade cars, with a source retroactively \u2013 and unofficially \u2013 calling it the ''Thomassima Zero''.<ref name=oct/><ref name=\":1\" />{{rp|91}}{{efn|Some sources incorrectly calls this car the actual Thomassima I, making it the car which was lost in Florence<ref name=mom/>}}\n\nThe ''Thomassima I'' was made under the request of a unknown Swiss baron who sought a replacement for his [[Corvette C2|Corvette]] in order to remain competitive against the [[Shelby Cobra]]s.<ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} Meade based this \"anti-Cobra\" on a Ferrari 250 GT chassis fitted with a powerful Chevrolet V8 engine in its front,<ref name=rt/><ref name=mom/> and covered with a heavily altered bodywork which included [[Gull-wing door|gullwings]] that could have been removed and put into the car trunk, an idea which Meade considered unprecedented at the time.<ref name=mom/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}}\n\n[[File:1967 Ferrari 330 P3slash4, Glickenhaus (Lime Rock).jpg|thumb|The Ferrari 330 P3/P4. Meade's Thomassima II was his idea of how this Ferrari should have looked like]]\nThe ''Thomassima II''{{efn|Some older sources incorrectly calls this car the first Thomassima built.<ref name=rt/><ref name=ait>{{cite web |url=https://mycarquest.com/2016/05/tom-meade-americano-italia.html |title=Tom Meade: An Americano In Italia \u2013 Doing What All Of Us Wished We Could Do\u2026|last=Wyss |first=Wallace |date=1 May 2016 |website=mycarquest.com |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>}} was requested in late 1966 by Harry Windsor from [[Los Gatos, California]]. Windsor wanted a [[mid-engine car]] resembling the Ferrari 330 P3 or [[Ferrari 330 P4|P4]].<ref name=rt/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} Meade then proceeded to create his idea of how the P3/P4 should have looked like, but it proved very challenging.<ref name=oct/><br/>\nHe had to radically modify the frame of a [[Cooper T43]] [[Formula One]] car, and fitting it with a Ferrari 250 GT [[Ferrari Colombo engine|Colombo V12 engine]] coupled to a 4-speed [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] [[gearbox]].<ref name=rt/><ref name=ait/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}}<ref name=mom/> For the bodywork, Meade was greatly helped by [[Piero Drogo]] of [[Carrozzeria Sports Cars]]. The final result was ready in the 1967, and was a little longer and more muscular car than a P4, weighing less than {{convert|2000|lb|kg}} and sporting {{convert|240|hp|kW}}, with a [[Convertible#Detachable hardtop|detachable hardtop]].<ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}}<ref name=mom/> The Thomassima II was shipped to California where Windsor rebranded it as a \"Ferrari 250 P/4 Roadster\" and exhibited it at the 1968 [[Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance]] where it won a class award.<ref name=mom/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} Despite the fact that it was improperly called a Ferrari, the Thomassima II made Meade a well known figure in his field.<ref name=mom/> In 1971 the car made a cameo appearance in [[George Lucas]]\u2019 directorial debut film ''[[THX 1138]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Breeze |first=Joe |date=5 January 2015|title=The police drove Lola T70s in George Lucas\u2019s directorial debut |url=https://www.classicdriver.com/en/article/cars/police-drove-lola-t70s-george-lucass-directorial-debut |magazine=Classic Driver |location= |publisher=}}</ref> In later times the car was crashed, then purchased in the early 1980s by Larry Hatfield and later restored. It starred at the 2015 [[Monterey Car Week#Concorso Italiano|Concorso Italiano at Monterey]].<ref name=mom/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} As of December 2016, the car is still in Hatfield's possession.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Stone |first=Matt |date=8 December 2016|title=Mimicking Maranello |url=https://www.forza-mag.com/issues/155/articles/mimicking-maranello |magazine=Forza |issue=155 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Thomassima III'' was built not before the 1968, and its completion required over a year of work.<ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}}<ref name=rt/> The donor car was a 1958 [[Ferrari 250#250 GT Coup\u00e9 Pinin Farina|Ferrari 250 GT Pininfarina Coup\u00e9]] (chassis number 1065GT) powered by a [[Ferrari Colombo engine#250|3L V12 engine]]. The gearbox was replaced with a 5-speed ZF and the brakes were upgraded.<ref name=rt/><ref name=ait/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91}} The bodywork was altered dramatically, even further than the earlier \"Thomassima Zero\", resulting in an extremely low, muscular, front-engined coupe featuring gullwings, twisted exhausts on both sides and [[centerlock wheel]]s. Interiors were lavish, with a steel-casted steering wheel. Meade claimed to have put a particular emphasis into the finish.<ref name=rt/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|91\u20132}}<ref name=mom/> The Thomassima III was the car that brought Meade the most fame, and he often used it for promoting himself. He considered it his masterpiece and decided not to sell it to anyone.<ref name=rt/><ref name=mom/> In December 1970 it was featured on ''Road & Track'', appeared on Italian TV, ''[[60 Minutes]]''<ref name=60min>{{Cite episode |title=Tom Meade |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jazEBNIV7K8 |access-date=19 April 2020 |series=60 Minutes |series-link= |first=Winston |last=Burdett |network=CBS |date=1970}}</ref> and on [[Walter Cronkite]]'s talk show, won awards in car shows in Italy and USA, and became a [[Hot Wheels]] scale model.<ref name=rt/><ref name=ait/><ref name=oct/>{{rp|92}} Prior to Meade's departure from Italy, the Thomassima III was placed in long-term storage in a facility near Lake Como, Italy.<ref name=\"mom\" /> It was exhibited at the [[Museo Ferrari]] in Maranello during 2014, as part of the \"California Dreaming\" exhibition.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.velocetoday.com/california-dreaming-at-the-ferrari-museum/|title=California Dreaming at the Ferrari Museum|last=Sharp|first=Jonathan|date=25 November 2014|website=www.velocetoday.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> As of March 2020, the Thomassima III is owned by Meade's son and still kept in Italy.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=oct/>{{rp|94}}\n\n== Other projects ==\n\n[[File:1963 Ferrari 250 GT Lusso Fantuzzi (19630529192).jpg|alt=Ferrari 250 GT Lusso with modified bodywork by Fantuzzi and Meade|thumb|Ferrari 250 GT Lusso (chassis 4383GT) with modified bodywork by Fantuzzi and Meade]]\nIn addition to the ''Thomassima'' cars, Meade constructed multiple other custom cars with the help of his Italian collaborators. These included the [[Neri and Bonacini#Ferrari Nembo|Nembo series]] of Ferrari 250 GT-based road cars, built in collaboration with Neri and Bonacini. Three Nembo spiders and one Nembo coupe were built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/lotfinder/lot/1960-ferrari-250-gt-nembo-spyder-4554166-details.aspx|title=1960 FERRARI 250 GT 'NEMBO SPYDER'|website=www.christies.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Sonnery|first=Marc|date=1998-04-25|title=The Nembo Ferraris - Part I|url=|journal=Ferrari Market Letter|volume=23|issue=9|pages=1\u20135|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=Jonathan|date=November 1966|title=Neri and Bonacini|url=|journal=Road & Track|volume=18|issue=3|pages=42\u201344|via=}}</ref>\n\nMeade modified 7 or 8 [[Ferrari 250 GT Lusso]]<nowiki/>s with [[Ferrari 330 LMB|330 LMB]]-style front bodywork, including triple \"nostril\"-style air intakes and/or aerodynamic covered headlights. These cars were mostly purchased in wrecked or non-working condition from the [[Emilia-Romagna|Emilia-Romagna region]] near Modena, rebuilt and modified then resold.<ref name=\"mom\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journal.classiccars.com/2017/12/16/meade-modena-cars-sculptures-personal-expression/|title=Meade of Modena: Cars as sculptures of personal expression|last=Crane|first=Larry|date=2017-12-17|website=ClassicCars.com Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fantasyjunction.com/sold/1963-ferrari-250gt-lusso-speciale-by-fantuzzi/overview|title=1963 Ferrari 250GT Lusso Speciale by Fantuzzi|last=|first=|date=|website=www.fantasyjunction.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barchetta.cc/english/All.Ferraris/Detail/4587GT.250.GTL.htm|title=250 GT Lusso s/n 4587GT|website=www.barchetta.cc|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barchetta.cc/english/All.Ferraris/Detail/4383GT.250.GTL.htm|title=250 GT Lusso s/n 4383GT|website=www.barchetta.cc|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><br />\n\n== Later life ==\nAfter leaving Italy sometime during the 1970s, Meade spent approximately two decades traveling in Asia. In 1993, Meade returned to Los Angeles in order to take care of his mother. He began planning the construction of a ''Thomassima IV'' (sometimes styled ''Thomassima IIII''), which was to have a [[Carbon fiber reinforced polymer|carbon fiber]] body and a [[Ferrari 333 SP]] engine.<ref name=\"mom\" /><ref name=\"ait\" />\n\nMeade died in August 2013.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://drive-my.com/en/retro-carss/item/4096-1969-thomassima-iii.html|title=1969 Thomassima III|last=Sonnery|first=Marc|date=31 January 2020|website=Drive|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nMeade had an adopted son, who maintains his estate and works in the luxury goods industry.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><br />\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meade, Tom}}\n[[:Category:Ferrari people]]\n[[:Category:Maserati people]]\n[[:Category:Coachbuilders of Italy]]\n[[:Category:Vehicle modification people]]\n[[:Category:1938 births]]\n[[:Category:2013 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Prova MO", "label": "safe", "comment": "enable categories and remove draft template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Meade"}
{"title_page": "Rubus idaeus", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Malina.jpg\n|image_caption = Fruit on a wild raspberry, Czech Republic\n|subgenus = [[Rubus subg. Idaeobatus|Idaeobatus]]\n|taxon = Rubus idaeus\n|authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]] 1753 not Blanco 1837 nor Vell. 1829 nor Pursh 1814 nor Thunb. 1784\n|synonyms_ref=<ref>{{ThePlantList |id=rjp-310 |taxon=Rubus idaeus |authority=L.}}</ref>\n|synonyms={{collapsible list|bullets = true\n|title=<small>Synonymy</small>\n|''Batidaea idea'' <small>(L.) Nieuwl.</small>\n|''Batidaea vulgaris'' <small>Nieuwl.</small>\n|''Batidea peramoena'' <small>Greene</small>\n|''Rubus acanthocladus'' <small>Borb</small>\n|''Rubus buschii'' <small>(Rozanova) Grossh.</small>\n|''Rubus chrysocarpus'' <small>\u010celak. ex Gyer</small>\n|''Rubus euroasiaticus'' <small>Sinkova</small>\n|''Rubus fragrans'' <small>Salisb.</small>\n|''Rubus frambaesianus'' <small>Lam.</small>\n|''Rubus glaber'' <small>Mill. ex Simonk.</small>\n|''Rubus greeneanus'' <small>L.H.Bailey</small> \n|''Rubus leesii'' <small>Bab.</small>\n|''Rubus obtusifolius'' <small>Willd. </small>\n|''Rubus sericeus'' <small>Gilib.</small>\n|''Rubus vulgatus'' <small>Rozanova</small>\n|''Rubus komarovii'' <small>Nakai</small>\n|''Rubus melanolasius'' <small>(Dieck ex Focke) Kom.</small>\n|''Rubus sachalinensis'' <small>H.L\u00e9v.</small>\n|''Rubus sibiricus'' <small>(Kom.) Sinkova</small>\n|''Rubus nipponicus'' <small>(Focke) Koidz.</small>\n|''Batidea acalyphacea'' <small>Greene </small>\n|''Batidea arizonica'' <small>Greene</small>\n|''Rubus carolinianus'' <small>Rydb.</small> \n|''Rubus melanolasius'' <small>Dieck</small> \n|''Rubus neglectus'' <small>Peck</small>\n|''Rubus strigosus'' <small>Michx.</small>\n|''Batidea viburnifolia'' <small>Greene</small>\n}}}}\n'''''Rubus idaeus''''' ('''[[raspberry]]''', also called '''red raspberry''' or occasionally as '''European raspberry''' to distinguish it from other raspberries) is a red-fruited species of ''[[Rubus]]'' native to Europe and northern Asia and commonly cultivated in other [[temperate]] regions.<ref name=fe>{{cite web |website=Flora Europaea |url=http://rbg-web2.rbge.org.uk/cgi-bin/nph-readbtree.pl/feout?GENUS_XREF=Rubus+&SPECIES_XREF=idaeus |title=''Rubus idaeus''}}</ref><ref name=grin>{{GRIN | accessdate = 15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nA closely related plant in North America, sometimes regarded as the [[variety (biology)|variety]] ''Rubus idaeus'' var. ''strigosus'', is more commonly treated as a distinct species, ''[[Rubus strigosus]]'' (American red raspberry), as is done here.<ref name=grin2>{{GRIN | ''Rubus idaeus'' var. ''strigosus'' | 32351 | accessdate = 15 December 2017}}</ref> Red-fruited cultivated raspberries, even in North America, are generally ''Rubus idaeus'' or horticultural derivatives of hybrids of ''R. idaeus'' and ''R. strigosus;'' these plants are all addressed in the present article.\n\n==Description==\nPlants of ''Rubus idaeus'' are generally [[perennial plant|perennials]] which bear [[biennial plant|biennial]] stems (\"canes\") from a perennial root system. In its first year, a new, unbranched stem (\"[[primocane]]\") grows vigorously to its full height of 1.5\u20132.5 m (5.0\u20138.3 feet), bearing large [[pinnately compound]] [[leaves]] with five or seven leaflets, but usually no flowers. In its second year (as a \"[[floricane]]\"), a stem does not grow taller, but produces several side shoots, which bear smaller leaves with three or five leaflets. The [[flower]]s are produced in late spring on short [[raceme]]s on the tips of these side shoots, each flower about 1&nbsp;cm (0.4 inches) diameter with five white [[petal]]s. The [[fruit]] is red, edible, and sweet but tart-flavoured, produced in summer or early autumn; in [[botanical]] terminology, it is not a [[Berry (botany)|berry]] at all, but an [[aggregate fruit]] of numerous [[drupelet]]s around a central core. In raspberries (various species of [[Rubus subg. Idaeobatus|''Rubus'' subgenus ''Idaeobatus'']]), the drupelets separate from the core when picked, leaving a hollow fruit, whereas in [[blackberry|blackberries]] and most other species of ''Rubus,'' the drupelets stay attached to the core.<ref name=fnwe>{{cite web |website=Flora of NW Europe |url=http://ip30.eti.uva.nl/BIS/flora.php?selected=beschrijving&menuentry=soorten&id=2609 |title=''Rubus idaeus''}}</ref><ref name=foc>{{eFloras|2|200011446|Rubus idaeus |family=Rosaceae |last1=Lu |first1=Lingdi<!-- surname given first? --> |first2=David E. |last2=Boufford}}</ref><ref name=blamey>{{cite book |last1=Blamey |first1=M. |last2=Grey-Wilson |first2=C. |date=1989 |title=Flora of Britain and Northern Europe |isbn=0-340-40170-2}}.</ref><ref name=rhs>{{cite book |editor-last=Huxley |editor-first=A. |date=1992 |title=New RHS Dictionary of Gardening |publisher=Macmillan |isbn=0-333-47494-5}}.</ref>\n\n==Biotope==\nAs a wild plant, ''R. idaeus'' typically grows in forests, forming open stands under a tree canopy, and denser stands in clearings. In the south of its range (southern Europe and central Asia), it only occurs at high altitudes in mountains.<ref name=blamey/> The species name ''idaeus'' refers to its occurrence on [[Mount Ida (Turkey)|Mount Ida]] near Troy in northwest Turkey, where the ancient Greeks were most familiar with it.<ref name=rhs/>\n\n==Cultivation and uses==\n[[File:Activity on a leaf on a red raspberry bush.jpg|thumb|A red raspberry plant in a nursery in [[Cranford, New Jersey]].]]\n[[File:Red raspberries in a bowl.jpg|thumb|right|A bowl of fresh-picked wild red raspberries in Riverdale, New Jersey.]]\n''R. idaeus'' is grown primarily for its fruits, but occasionally for its leaves, roots, or other parts.\n\n===Fruits===\n{{Main|Raspberry}}\nThe fruit of ''R. idaeus'' is an important food crop, though most modern commercial raspberry [[cultivar]]s derive from [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrids]] between ''R. idaeus'' and ''R. strigosus''.<ref name=rhs/> The fruits of wild plants have a sweet taste and are very aromatic.\n\n===Leaves and other parts===\n{{Main|Red raspberry leaf}}\nRed raspberries contains 31 \u03bcg/100 g of folate.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Martin |first1=H |last2=Comeskey |first2=D |last3=Simpson |first3=RM |last4=Laing |first4=WA |last5=McGhie |first5=TK |year=2010 |title=Quantification of folate in fruits and vegetables: a fluorescence-based homogeneous assay |url= |journal=Anal Biochem |volume=402 |issue=2 |pages=137\u2013145 |doi=10.1016/j.ab.2010.03.032}}</ref> Red raspberries have antioxidant effects that play a minor role in the killing of stomach and colon cancer cells.<ref>''Nutr Res.''  30(11):777-782</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=McDougall |first1=GJ |last2=Ross |first2=HA |last3=Ikeji |first3=M |last4=Stewart |first4=D |year=2008 |title=Berry extracts exert different antiproliferative effects against cervical and colon cancer cells grown in vitro |url= |journal=[[J Agric Food Chem]] |volume=56 |issue=9 |pages=3016\u20133023 |doi=10.1021/jf073469n}}</ref>\n\nYoung roots of ''Rubus idaeus'' prevented kidney stone formation in a mouse model of [[hyperoxaluria]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ghalayini |first1=IF |last2=Al-Ghazo |first2=MA |last3=Harfeil |first3=MN |year=2011 |title=Prophylaxis and therapeutic effects of raspberry (''Rubus idaeus'') on renal stone formation in Balb/c mice |url= |journal=Int Braz J Urol |volume=37 |issue=2 |pages=259\u2013267 }}</ref> [http://www.rdchemicals.com/chemicals.php?mode=details&mol_id=8291 Tiliroside] from raspberry is a potent [[tyrosinase]] inhibitor and might be used as a skin-whitening agent and pigmentation medicine.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lu |first1=YH |last2=Chen |first2=J |last3=Wei |first3=DZ |last4=Wang |first4=ZT |last5=Tao |first5=XY |year=2009 |title=Tyrosinase inhibitory effect and inhibitory mechanism of tiliroside from raspberry |url= |journal=J Enzyme Inhib Med Chem. |volume=24 |issue=5 |pages=1154\u20131160 |doi=10.1080/14756360802694252|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nRaspberry fruit may protect the liver.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gi\u00e3o |first1=MS |last2=Pestana |first2=D |last3=Faria |first3=A |last4=Guimar\u00e3es |first4=JT |last5=Pintado |first5=ME |last6=Calhau |first6=C |last7=Azevedo |first7=I |last8=Malcata |first8=FX |year=2010 |title=Effects of extracts of selected medicinal plants upon hepatic oxidative stress |url= |journal=J Med Food |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=131\u2013136 |doi=10.1089/jmf.2008.0323}}</ref>\n\n==Chemistry==\n[[Vitamin C]] and phenolics are present in red raspberries. Most notably, the anthocyanins cyanidin-3-sophoroside, cyanidin-3-(2(G)-glucosylrutinoside) and [[cyanidin-3-glucoside]], the two ellagitannins [[sanguiin H-6]] and [[lambertianin C]] are present together with trace levels of flavonols, [[ellagic acid]] and [[hydroxycinnamate]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Mullen |first1=W. |last2=Stewart |first2=A. J. |last3=Lean |first3=M. E. |last4=Gardner |first4=P. |last5=Duthie |first5=G. G. |last6=Crozier |first6=A. |title=Effect of freezing and storage on the phenolics, ellagitannins, flavonoids, and antioxidant capacity of red raspberries |journal=Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry |volume=50 |issue=18 |pages=5197\u20135201 |year=2002 |pmid=12188629 |doi=10.1021/jf020141f }}</ref>\n\n[[Polyphenol]]ic compounds from raspberry seeds have [[antioxidant effect of polyphenols|antioxidant]] effects [[in vitro]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Godevac |first1=D |last2=Tesevi\u0107 |first2=V |last3=Vajs |first3=V |last4=Milosavljevi\u0107 |first4=S |last5=Stankovi\u0107 |first5=M |year=2009 |title=Antioxidant properties of raspberry seed extracts on micronucleus distribution in peripheral blood lymphocytes |url= |journal=Food Chem Toxicol |volume=47 |issue=11 |pages=2853\u20132859 |doi=10.1016/j.fct.2009.09.006}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Aiyer |first1=HS |last2=Kichambare |first2=S |last3=Gupta |first3=RC |year=2008 |title=Prevention of oxidative DNA damage by bioactive berry components |url= |journal=Nutr Cancer |volume=60 |issue=Suppl 1 |pages=36\u201342 }}</ref> but have no proven antioxidant effect in humans.<ref name=\"Gross\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nutraceuticalsworld.com/issues/2009-03/view_features/new-roles-for-polyphenols/ |title=New Roles for Polyphenols. A 3-Part report on Current Regulations & the State of Science |last1=Gross |first1=P |last2= |first2= |year=2009 |work=Nutraceuticals World |publisher=Rodman Media |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref> [[Raspberry ketone]]s are derived from various fruits and plants, not raspberries, and are marketed as having weight loss benefits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fic.osu.edu/members/spotlight/the-sweet-taste-of-weight-loss.html/|publisher=Ohio State University Food Innovation Center|accessdate=3 Sep 2014|title=The Sweet Taste of Weight Loss|date=2014}}</ref> There is no clinical evidence for this effect in humans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.webmd.com/vitamins-supplements/ingredientmono-1262-RASPBERRY%20KETONE.aspx?activeIngredientId=1262 |title=Raspberry Ketone |publisher=[[WebMD]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chambord Liqueur]] \u2013 is an infusion of red and black raspberries, Madagascar [[vanilla]] and [[XO cognac]]\n* [[List of culinary fruits]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cookbook|Raspberry}}\n* {{Wikispecies-inline|Rubus idaeus}}\n* {{Commons-inline|Rubus idaeus}}\n* {{cite EB1911|wstitle=Raspberry |volume=22 |short=x}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q12252383}}\n\n[[Category:Rubus|idaeus]]\n[[Category:Berries]]\n[[Category:Flora of Europe]]\n[[Category:Flora of Asia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n[[Category:Subshrubs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Malina.jpg\n|image_caption = Fruit on a wild raspberry, Czech Republic\n|subgenus = [[Rubus subg. Idaeobatus|Idaeobatus]]\n|taxon = Rubus idaeus\n|authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]] 1753 not Blanco 1837 nor Vell. 1829 nor Pursh 1814 nor Thunb. 1784\n|synonyms_ref=<ref>{{ThePlantList |id=rjp-310 |taxon=Rubus idaeus |authority=L.}}</ref>\n|synonyms={{collapsible list|bullets = true\n|title=<small>Synonymy</small>\n|''Batidaea idea'' <small>(L.) Nieuwl.</small>\n|''Batidaea vulgaris'' <small>Nieuwl.</small>\n|''Batidea peramoena'' <small>Greene</small>\n|''Rubus acanthocladus'' <small>Borb</small>\n|''Rubus buschii'' <small>(Rozanova) Grossh.</small>\n|''Rubus chrysocarpus'' <small>\u010celak. ex Gyer</small>\n|''Rubus euroasiaticus'' <small>Sinkova</small>\n|''Rubus fragrans'' <small>Salisb.</small>\n|''Rubus frambaesianus'' <small>Lam.</small>\n|''Rubus glaber'' <small>Mill. ex Simonk.</small>\n|''Rubus greeneanus'' <small>L.H.Bailey</small> \n|''Rubus leesii'' <small>Bab.</small>\n|''Rubus obtusifolius'' <small>Willd. </small>\n|''Rubus sericeus'' <small>Gilib.</small>\n|''Rubus vulgatus'' <small>Rozanova</small>\n|''Rubus komarovii'' <small>Nakai</small>\n|''Rubus melanolasius'' <small>(Dieck ex Focke) Kom.</small>\n|''Rubus sachalinensis'' <small>H.L\u00e9v.</small>\n|''Rubus sibiricus'' <small>(Kom.) Sinkova</small>\n|''Rubus nipponicus'' <small>(Focke) Koidz.</small>\n|''Batidea acalyphacea'' <small>Greene </small>\n|''Batidea arizonica'' <small>Greene</small>\n|''Rubus carolinianus'' <small>Rydb.</small> \n|''Rubus melanolasius'' <small>Dieck</small> \n|''Rubus neglectus'' <small>Peck</small>\n|''Rubus strigosus'' <small>Michx.</small>\n|''Batidea viburnifolia'' <small>Greene</small>\n}}}}\n'''''Rubus idaeus''''' ('''[[raspberry]]''', also called '''red raspberry''' or  occasionally as '''European raspberry''' to distinguish it from other raspberries) is a red-fruited species of ''[[Rubus]]'' native to Europe and northern Asia and commonly cultivated in other [[temperate]] regions.<ref name=fe>{{cite web |website=Flora Europaea |url=http://rbg-web2.rbge.org.uk/cgi-bin/nph-readbtree.pl/feout?GENUS_XREF=Rubus+&SPECIES_XREF=idaeus |title=''Rubus idaeus''}}</ref><ref name=grin>{{GRIN | accessdate = 15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nA closely related plant in North America, sometimes regarded as the [[variety (biology)|variety]] ''Rubus idaeus'' var. ''strigosus'', is more commonly treated as a distinct species, ''[[Rubus strigosus]]'' (American red raspberry), as is done here.<ref name=grin2>{{GRIN | ''Rubus idaeus'' var. ''strigosus'' | 32351 | accessdate = 15 December 2017}}</ref>  Red-fruited cultivated raspberries, even in North America, are generally ''Rubus idaeus'' or horticultural derivatives of hybrids of ''R. idaeus'' and ''R. strigosus;'' these plants are all addressed in the present article.\n\n==Description==\nPlants of ''Rubus idaeus'' are generally [[perennial plant|perennials]] which bear [[biennial plant|biennial]] stems (\"canes\") from a perennial root system. In its first year, a new, unbranched stem (\"[[primocane]]\") grows vigorously to its full height of 1.5\u20132.5 m (5.0\u20138.3 feet), bearing large [[pinnately compound]] [[leaves]] with five or seven leaflets, but usually no flowers. In its second year (as a \"[[floricane]]\"), a stem does not grow taller, but produces several side shoots, which bear smaller leaves with three or five leaflets. The [[flower]]s are produced in late spring on short [[raceme]]s on the tips of these side shoots, each flower about 1&nbsp;cm (0.4 inches) diameter with five white [[petal]]s. The [[fruit]] is red, edible, and sweet but tart-flavoured, produced in summer or early autumn; in [[botanical]] terminology, it is not a [[Berry (botany)|berry]] at all, but an [[aggregate fruit]] of numerous [[drupelet]]s around a central core. In raspberries (various species of [[Rubus subg. Idaeobatus|''Rubus'' subgenus ''Idaeobatus'']]), the drupelets separate from the core when picked, leaving a hollow fruit, whereas in [[blackberry|blackberries]] and most other species of ''Rubus,'' the drupelets stay attached to the core.<ref name=fnwe>{{cite web |website=Flora of NW Europe |url=http://ip30.eti.uva.nl/BIS/flora.php?selected=beschrijving&menuentry=soorten&id=2609 |title=''Rubus idaeus''}}</ref><ref name=foc>{{eFloras|2|200011446|Rubus idaeus |family=Rosaceae |last1=Lu |first1=Lingdi<!-- surname given first? --> |first2=David E. |last2=Boufford}}</ref><ref name=blamey>{{cite book |last1=Blamey |first1=M. |last2=Grey-Wilson |first2=C. |date=1989 |title=Flora of Britain and Northern Europe |isbn=0-340-40170-2}}.</ref><ref name=rhs>{{cite book |editor-last=Huxley |editor-first=A. |date=1992 |title=New RHS Dictionary of Gardening |publisher=Macmillan |isbn=0-333-47494-5}}.</ref>\n\n==Biotope==\nAs a wild plant, ''R. idaeus'' typically grows in forests, forming open stands under a tree canopy, and denser stands in clearings. In the south of its range (southern Europe and central Asia), it only occurs at high altitudes in mountains.<ref name=blamey/> The species name ''idaeus'' refers to its occurrence on [[Mount Ida (Turkey)|Mount Ida]] near Troy in northwest Turkey, where the ancient Greeks were most familiar with it.<ref name=rhs/>\n\n==Cultivation and uses==\n[[File:Activity on a leaf on a red raspberry bush.jpg|thumb|A red raspberry plant in a nursery in [[Cranford, New Jersey]].]]\n[[File:Red raspberries in a bowl.jpg|thumb|right|A bowl of fresh-picked wild red raspberries in Riverdale, New Jersey.]]\n''R. idaeus'' is grown primarily for its fruits, but occasionally for its leaves, roots, or other parts.\n\n===Fruits===\n{{Main|Raspberry}}\nThe fruit of ''R. idaeus'' is an important food crop, though most modern commercial raspberry [[cultivar]]s derive from [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrids]] between ''R. idaeus'' and ''R. strigosus''.<ref name=rhs/> The fruits of wild plants have a sweet taste and are very aromatic.\n\n===Leaves and other parts===\n{{Main|Red raspberry leaf}}\nRed raspberries contains 31 \u03bcg/100 g of folate.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Martin |first1=H |last2=Comeskey |first2=D |last3=Simpson |first3=RM |last4=Laing |first4=WA |last5=McGhie |first5=TK |year=2010 |title=Quantification of folate in fruits and vegetables: a fluorescence-based homogeneous assay |url= |journal=Anal Biochem |volume=402 |issue=2 |pages=137\u2013145 |doi=10.1016/j.ab.2010.03.032}}</ref>  Red raspberries have antioxidant effects that play a minor role in the killing of stomach and colon cancer cells.<ref>''Nutr Res.''  30(11):777-782</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=McDougall |first1=GJ |last2=Ross |first2=HA |last3=Ikeji |first3=M |last4=Stewart |first4=D |year=2008 |title=Berry extracts exert different antiproliferative effects against cervical and colon cancer cells grown in vitro |url= |journal=[[J Agric Food Chem]] |volume=56 |issue=9 |pages=3016\u20133023 |doi=10.1021/jf073469n}}</ref>\n\nYoung roots of ''Rubus idaeus'' prevented kidney stone formation in a mouse model of [[hyperoxaluria]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ghalayini |first1=IF |last2=Al-Ghazo |first2=MA |last3=Harfeil |first3=MN |year=2011 |title=Prophylaxis and therapeutic effects of raspberry (''Rubus idaeus'') on renal stone formation in Balb/c mice |url= |journal=Int Braz J Urol |volume=37 |issue=2 |pages=259\u2013267 }}</ref>\n[http://www.rdchemicals.com/chemicals.php?mode=details&mol_id=8291 Tiliroside] from raspberry is a potent [[tyrosinase]] inhibitor and might be used as a skin-whitening agent and pigmentation medicine.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lu |first1=YH |last2=Chen |first2=J |last3=Wei |first3=DZ |last4=Wang |first4=ZT |last5=Tao |first5=XY |year=2009 |title=Tyrosinase inhibitory effect and inhibitory mechanism of tiliroside from raspberry |url= |journal=J Enzyme Inhib Med Chem. |volume=24 |issue=5 |pages=1154\u20131160 |doi=10.1080/14756360802694252|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nRaspberry fruit may protect the liver.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gi\u00e3o |first1=MS |last2=Pestana |first2=D |last3=Faria |first3=A |last4=Guimar\u00e3es |first4=JT |last5=Pintado |first5=ME |last6=Calhau |first6=C |last7=Azevedo |first7=I |last8=Malcata |first8=FX |year=2010 |title=Effects of extracts of selected medicinal plants upon hepatic oxidative stress |url= |journal=J Med Food |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=131\u2013136 |doi=10.1089/jmf.2008.0323}}</ref>\n\n==Chemistry==\n[[Vitamin C]] and phenolics are present in red raspberries. Most notably, the anthocyanins cyanidin-3-sophoroside, cyanidin-3-(2(G)-glucosylrutinoside) and [[cyanidin-3-glucoside]], the two ellagitannins [[sanguiin H-6]] and [[lambertianin C]] are present together with trace levels of flavonols, [[ellagic acid]] and [[hydroxycinnamate]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Mullen |first1=W. |last2=Stewart |first2=A. J. |last3=Lean |first3=M. E. |last4=Gardner |first4=P. |last5=Duthie |first5=G. G. |last6=Crozier |first6=A. |title=Effect of freezing and storage on the phenolics, ellagitannins, flavonoids, and antioxidant capacity of red raspberries |journal=Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry |volume=50 |issue=18 |pages=5197\u20135201 |year=2002 |pmid=12188629 |doi=10.1021/jf020141f }}</ref>\n\n[[Polyphenol]]ic compounds from raspberry seeds have [[antioxidant effect of polyphenols|antioxidant]] effects [[in vitro]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Godevac |first1=D |last2=Tesevi\u0107 |first2=V |last3=Vajs |first3=V |last4=Milosavljevi\u0107 |first4=S |last5=Stankovi\u0107 |first5=M |year=2009 |title=Antioxidant properties of raspberry seed extracts on micronucleus distribution in peripheral blood lymphocytes |url= |journal=Food Chem Toxicol |volume=47 |issue=11 |pages=2853\u20132859 |doi=10.1016/j.fct.2009.09.006}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Aiyer |first1=HS |last2=Kichambare |first2=S |last3=Gupta |first3=RC |year=2008 |title=Prevention of oxidative DNA damage by bioactive berry components |url= |journal=Nutr Cancer |volume=60 |issue=Suppl 1 |pages=36\u201342 }}</ref> but have no proven antioxidant effect in humans.<ref name=\"Gross\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nutraceuticalsworld.com/issues/2009-03/view_features/new-roles-for-polyphenols/ |title=New Roles for Polyphenols. A 3-Part report on Current Regulations & the State of Science |last1=Gross |first1=P |last2= |first2= |year=2009 |work=Nutraceuticals World |publisher=Rodman Media |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref> [[Raspberry ketone]]s are derived from various fruits and plants, not raspberries, and are marketed as having weight loss benefits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fic.osu.edu/members/spotlight/the-sweet-taste-of-weight-loss.html/|publisher=Ohio State University Food Innovation Center|accessdate=3 Sep 2014|title=The Sweet Taste of Weight Loss|date=2014}}</ref> There is no clinical evidence for this effect in humans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.webmd.com/vitamins-supplements/ingredientmono-1262-RASPBERRY%20KETONE.aspx?activeIngredientId=1262 |title=Raspberry Ketone |publisher=[[WebMD]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chambord Liqueur]] \u2013 is an infusion of red and black raspberries, Madagascar [[vanilla]] and [[XO cognac]]\n* [[List of culinary fruits]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cookbook|Raspberry}}\n* {{Wikispecies-inline|Rubus idaeus}}\n* {{Commons-inline|Rubus idaeus}}\n* {{cite EB1911|wstitle=Raspberry |volume=22 |short=x}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q12252383}}\n\n[[Category:Rubus|idaeus]]\n[[Category:Berries]]\n[[Category:Flora of Europe]]\n[[Category:Flora of Asia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n[[Category:Subshrubs]]\n", "name_user": "Harrumphings", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed double spaces", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rubus_idaeus"}
{"title_page": "Milka Grgurova-Aleksi\u0107", "text_new": "'''Milka Aleksi\u0107 Grgurova''' ([[Sombor]], [[Habsburg Monarchy]], 14 February 1840 \u2014 [[Belgrade]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]], 25 March 1924)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ewUTAQAAMAAJ&q=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&dq=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiuw_CjgLvlAhUIXa0KHU11Dus4ChDoAQhpMAg|title=Hrvatska enciklopedija: O-Pre|first=Dalibor|last=Brozovi\u0107|date=January 31, 1999|publisher=Leksikografski zavod \"Miroslav Krle\u017ea\"|via=Google Books}}</ref>was a Serbian stage actress who starred in some of the most popular Serbian plays of the second half of the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, including the role of ''Ljubica'' in ''Mejrima'' by [[Matija Ban]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=OxrCtwAACAAJ&dq=mejrima+by+matija+ban&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu9Y2XpbPlAhUNMawKHdHIDLIQ6AEIKTAA|title=Mejrima ili Bo\u0161njaci: pozori\u0161tno d\u011blo u pet\u201d razd\u011bla|first=Matija|last=Ban|date=January 31, 1851|publisher=Nar. kn\u2019igope\u010datnija dra Dan. Medakovi\u0107a|via=Google Books}}</ref>, ''Posmrtna slava kneza Mihaila'' by [[Djordje Maleti\u0107]], [[Jaquinta of Bari|Jaquinta]], the wife of [[Constantine Bodin]], in the drama by the same name by [[Dragutin Ili\u0107]], and many more. She also starred in some of the most popular Serbian adaptations of plays by foreign playwrights, notably [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=AFQ8AAAAIAAJ&q=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&dq=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGk-zrgbvlAhUPiqwKHd4tBiE4FBDoAQgxMAE|title=\u0160ekspir i srpska drama u XIX veku|first=Du\u0161an|last=Mihailovi\u0107|date=January 31, 1984|publisher=Univerzitet umetnosti|via=Google Books}}</ref>Her contemporaries were actors [[Milo\u0161 Cveti\u0107]] and [[Pera Dobrinovi\u0107]].\n\nShe was born Milka Grgurov, daughter of Sofia and father Sava Grgurov, a wealthy Sombor merchant. As soon as she finished high school she married a man that her parents picked out for her. After the birth of her daughter and two years into the marriage she left her husband and came back to live with her parents with her daughter.\n\nShe always loved acting even as a child she imagined playing roles and now with most of her close friends involved in the Touring Amateur Theatre in Sobor, she began seriously considering it as a career. Although the theatre company included some of her relatives, Milka's parents initially disapproved of her choice of profession. At that time, acting was not generally accepted by everyone as a respectable profession, though a change was beginning to take place. Milka made her first amateur acting debut with the Sombor touring theatre company in early 1862. Her premiere was a success although she felt she needed to learn more about acting and the theatre. That same year she enrolled at a Women's College in Belgrade where she attended classes in literature and drama.{{sfn|\u0422\u043e\u043c\u0438\u045b|2014|pp=178}}\n\nIn 1864, Milka won her first professional success as ''Ljubica'' in Matija Ban's ''Mejrima''. This brought her to the attention of [[Jovan \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107]], who immediately signed her up as a member of the [[National Theatre in Belgrade]]. She was engaged to appear in all the theatrical productions scheduled for that season. There was no turning back for her and for the next 40 years her life was dedicated exclusively to the stage. \n\nShe traveled in all of our Serbian lands from [[Vojvodina]] which was part of the [[Habsburg Empire]] to [[Bosnia and Hercegovina]] which was part of another empire -- [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] -- and in [[Mostar]] she made a great impression on her Serbian public whether Orthodox or Muslim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=XaRAAQAAIAAJ&q=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&dq=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ns_73LflAhXIc98KHRIKBGwQ6AEIODAC|title=Pozori\u0161ni repertoar u Mostaru, 1879-2001: repertoari pozori\u0161ta, pozori\u0161nih dru\u017e\u030cina i grupa, pozori\u0161ta narodnog oslobo\u0111enja Hercegovine, festivala, smotri, susreta i gostovanja|first=Salko|last=\u0160ari\u0107|date=January 31, 2006|publisher=Selbstverl.|via=Google Books}}</ref>In 1903, she wrote about her experiences in Mostar in the magazine ''Bosanska Vila''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=TD4wAAAAMAAJ&q=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&dq=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimwdms_7rlAhVEcq0KHScoDGAQ6AEIajAI|title=Istorija pozori\u0161ta Bosne i Hercegovine|first=Josip|last=Le\u0161i\u0107|date=January 31, 1985|publisher=\"Svjetlost,\" OOUR Izdava\u010dka djelatnost|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nIn her career that spanned four decades, she performed in more than 400 roles on the stage.\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Serbian actresses]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grgurova-Aleksi\u0107, Milka}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Milka Aleksi\u0107 Grgurova''' ([[Sombor]], [[Habsburg Monarchy]], 14 February 1840 \u2014 [[Belgrade]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]], 25 March 1924)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ewUTAQAAMAAJ&q=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&dq=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiuw_CjgLvlAhUIXa0KHU11Dus4ChDoAQhpMAg|title=Hrvatska enciklopedija: O-Pre|first=Dalibor|last=Brozovi\u0107|date=January 31, 1999|publisher=Leksikografski zavod \"Miroslav Krle\u017ea\"|via=Google Books}}</ref>was a Serbian stage actress who starred in some of the most popular Serbian plays of the second half of the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, including the role of ''Ljubica'' in ''Mejrima'' by [[Matija Ban]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=OxrCtwAACAAJ&dq=mejrima+by+matija+ban&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu9Y2XpbPlAhUNMawKHdHIDLIQ6AEIKTAA|title=Mejrima ili Bo\u0161njaci: pozori\u0161tno d\u011blo u pet\u201d razd\u011bla|first=Matija|last=Ban|date=January 31, 1851|publisher=Nar. kn\u2019igope\u010datnija dra Dan. Medakovi\u0107a|via=Google Books}}</ref>, ''Posmrtna slava kneza Mihaila'' by [[Djordje Maleti\u0107]], [[Jaquinta of Bari|Jaquinta]], the wife of [[Constantine Bodin]], in the drama by the same name by [[Dragutin Ili\u0107]], and many more. She also starred in some of the most popular Serbian adaptations of plays by foreign playwrights, notably [[Shakespeare]]'s [[Romeo and Juliette]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=AFQ8AAAAIAAJ&q=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&dq=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGk-zrgbvlAhUPiqwKHd4tBiE4FBDoAQgxMAE|title=\u0160ekspir i srpska drama u XIX veku|first=Du\u0161an|last=Mihailovi\u0107|date=January 31, 1984|publisher=Univerzitet umetnosti|via=Google Books}}</ref>Her contemporaries were actors [[Milo\u0161 Cveti\u0107]] and [[Pera Dobrinovi\u0107]].\n\nShe was born Milka Grgurov, daughter of Sofia and father Sava Grgurov, a wealthy Sombor merchant. As soon as she finished high school she married a man that her parents picked out for her. After the birth of her daughter and two years into the marriage she left her husband and came back to live with her parents with her daughter.\n\nShe always loved acting even as a child she imagined playing roles and now with most of her close friends involved in the Touring Amateur Theatre in Sobor, she began seriously considering it as a career. Although the theatre company included some of her relatives, Milka's parents initially disapproved of her choice of profession. At that time, acting was not generally accepted by everyone as a respectable profession, though a change was beginning to take place. Milka made her first amateur acting debut with the Sombor touring theatre company in early 1862. Her premiere was a success although she felt she needed to learn more about acting and the theatre. That same year she enrolled at a Women's College in Belgrade where she attended classes in literature and drama.{{sfn|\u0422\u043e\u043c\u0438\u045b|2014|pp=178}}\n\nIn 1864, Milka won her first professional success as ''Ljubica'' in Matija Ban's ''Mejrima''. This brought her to the attention of [[Jovan \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107]], who immediately signed her up as a member of the [[National Theatre in Belgrade]]. She was engaged to appear in all the theatrical productions scheduled for that season. There was no turning back for her and for the next 40 years her life was dedicated exclusively to the stage. \n\nShe traveled in all of our Serbian lands from [[Vojvodina]] which was part of the [[Habsburg Empire]] to [[Bosnia and Hercegovina]] which was part of another empire -- [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] -- and in [[Mostar]] she made a great impression on her Serbian public whether Orthodox or Muslim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=XaRAAQAAIAAJ&q=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&dq=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ns_73LflAhXIc98KHRIKBGwQ6AEIODAC|title=Pozori\u0161ni repertoar u Mostaru, 1879-2001: repertoari pozori\u0161ta, pozori\u0161nih dru\u017e\u030cina i grupa, pozori\u0161ta narodnog oslobo\u0111enja Hercegovine, festivala, smotri, susreta i gostovanja|first=Salko|last=\u0160ari\u0107|date=January 31, 2006|publisher=Selbstverl.|via=Google Books}}</ref>In 1903, she wrote about her experiences in Mostar in the magazine ''Bosanska Vila''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=TD4wAAAAMAAJ&q=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&dq=Milka+Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimwdms_7rlAhVEcq0KHScoDGAQ6AEIajAI|title=Istorija pozori\u0161ta Bosne i Hercegovine|first=Josip|last=Le\u0161i\u0107|date=January 31, 1985|publisher=\"Svjetlost,\" OOUR Izdava\u010dka djelatnost|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nIn her career that spanned four decades, she performed in more than 400 roles on the stage.\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Serbian actresses]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grgurova-Aleksi\u0107, Milka}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo, italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milka_Grgurova-Aleksi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "South Carolina Highway 700", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=SC\n|type=SC\n|route=700\n|alternate_name=Maybank Highway\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-lat=32.689|frame-long=-80.083|zoom=10|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/South Carolina Highway 700}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|length_mi=20.38\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\"/>\n|established=\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a=[[Dead end (street)|Dead end]] in [[Rockville, South Carolina|Rockville]]\n|junction={{Jct|state=SC|SC|171}} in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=SC|US|17}} in Charleston\n|counties=[[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|previous_type=SC\n|previous_route=692\n|next_type=SC\n|next_route=702\n}}\n\n'''South Carolina Highway 700''' ('''SC 700''') is a [[state highway]] in the U.S. state of [[South Carolina]]. Known for most of its length as the Maybank Highway, the state highway runs {{convert|20.38|mi|km}} from a [[Dead end (street)|dead end]] in [[Rockville, South Carolina|Rockville]] east to [[U.S. Route 17 in South Carolina|U.S. Highway 17]] (US 17) in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]. SC 700 connects Charleston with [[James Island (South Carolina)|James Island]], [[Johns Island, South Carolina|Johns Island]], and [[Wadmalaw Island]] in southwestern [[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston County]].\n\n==Route description==\nSC 700 begins at a dead end in the town of Rockville on Wadmalaw Island. The terminus is on the north side of Bohicket Creek, which separates Wadmalaw Island from [[Seabrook Island]], a short distance east of Bohicket Creek's mouth on the [[Edisto River|North Edisto River]]. The state highway heads northeast as Maybank Highway, a two-lane road that passes by the [[Charleston Tea Plantation]], the only working tea plantation in the United States, and near the [[Firefly Distillery]], which is on Bear Bluff Road on the portion of the island north of Leadenwah Creek. SR 700 crosses Church Creek onto Johns Island, enters an outlying section of the city of Charleston, and arrives at the main crossroads of the island near the site of the venerable [[Angel Oak]]. Main Road heads north from the junction through the northern part of the island before crossing the [[Stono River]] on the [[John F. Limehouse Memorial Bridge]] to meet US 17 between [[Rantowles, South Carolina|Rantowles]] and Charleston. Bohicket Road heads south toward Seabrook Island and Kiawah Island. SC 700 continues east and near the eastern end of the island intersects River Road, which leads south to [[Charleston Executive Airport]].<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\"/>\n\nSC 700 expands to four lanes and crosses Pennys Creek and the Stono River on the high-level [[Paul Gelegotis Bridge]] and enters James Island. The highway passes through a golf course and along the south side of the historic [[Riverland Terrace]] neighborhood. SC 700 continues into a commercial area where the highway has a [[wye (rail)|wye]]-type junction with [[South Carolina Highway 171|SC 171]] (Folly Road) west of the [[McLeod Plantation]] and Charleston Country Club. Old Folly Road is used for the movements from eastbound SC 700 to southbound SC 171 and from northbound SC 171 to westbound SC 700. SC 700 and SC 171 head north concurrently on Folly Road, which has two lanes northbound and three lanes southbound. The highways enter the [[West Ashley]] section of Charleston by crossing Wappoo Creek, part of the [[Intracoastal Waterway]], on a [[Wappoo Creek Bridge|drawbridge]] named for [[Burnet R. Maybank]]. SC 700 and SC 171 diverge at a directional intersection that does not allow access from southbound SR 171 to eastbound SC 700. SC 171 heads north as Wesley Drive and is used to access southbound US 17 (Savannah Highway) and [[South Carolina Highway 61|SC 61]] (St. Andrews Boulevard). SC 700 heads northeast as five-lane Folly Road (three lanes westbound and two lanes eastbound) to its eastern terminus at a partial interchange with US 17 just west of the U.S. Highway's interchange with SC 61 and its bridges over the [[Ashley River (South Carolina)|Ashley River]]. The interchange allows access between SC 700 and US 17 in the direction of the peninsular section of Charleston.<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\"/>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\"/>|state=SC|county=Charleston}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Rockville\n|mile=0.00\n|road=[[Dead end (street)|Dead end]]\n|notes=Western terminus\n}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Charleston\n|lspan=3\n|mile=18.99\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=south|name1=Folly Road|city1=Folly Beach}}\n|notes=Western end of SC&nbsp;171 concurrency\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=19.96\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=north|name1=Wesley Drive|to2=y|US|17|dir2=south|SC|61|city1=North Charleston|location2=[[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]]}}\n|notes=Eastern end of SC&nbsp;171 concurrency\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=20.38\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=SC|US|17|dir1=north|name1=Savannah Highway|city1=Charleston|city2=Mount Pleasant}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus; southbound exit from and northbound entrance to US&nbsp;17\n}}\n{{Jctbtm|keys=concur,incomplete}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\">{{cite map|publisher=[[South Carolina Department of Transportation]]|title=Highways - Zipped Shapefile of roads maintained by SCDOT - Statewide|url=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/GIS/Statewide_Highways_2012.zip|format=ESRI shapefile|year=2012|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=S+Carolina+700+E&daddr=Folly+Rd&hl=en&sll=32.600952,-80.192868&sspn=0.00442,0.010568&geocode=FVxv8QEdGFU4-w%3BFTQv9AEd2Mg7-w&t=h&mra=ls&z=11|title=South Carolina Highway 700|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\">{{cite web|url=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/default.aspx|title=General County Highway Maps|publisher=South Carolina Department of Transportation|accessdate=2012-05-31}}\n*[http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/County/Charleston_County.pdf Charleston County] (PDF)\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML}}\n{{commonscat}}\n*[http://www.angelfire.com/sc3/scroads/sc700-709.html#sc700 The Highways of South Carolina: SC 700]\n\n[[Category:State highways in South Carolina|700]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston County, South Carolina|South Carolina Highway 700]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston, South Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=SC\n|type=SC\n|route=700\n|alternate_name=Maybank Highway\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-lat=32.689|frame-long=-80.083|zoom=10|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/South Carolina Highway 700}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|length_mi=20.38\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\"/>\n|established=\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a=[[Dead end (street)|Dead end]] in [[Rockville, South Carolina|Rockville]]\n|junction={{Jct|state=SC|SC|171}} in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=SC|US|17}} in Charleston\n|counties=[[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|previous_type=SC\n|previous_route=692\n|next_type=SC\n|next_route=702\n}}\n\n'''South Carolina Highway 700''' ('''SC 700''') is a [[state highway]] in the U.S. state of [[South Carolina]]. Known for most of its length as Maybank Highway, the state highway runs {{convert|20.38|mi|km}} from a [[Dead end (street)|dead end]] in [[Rockville, South Carolina|Rockville]] east to [[U.S. Route 17 in South Carolina|U.S. Highway 17]] (US 17) in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]. SC 700 connects Charleston with [[James Island (South Carolina)|James Island]], [[Johns Island, South Carolina|Johns Island]], and [[Wadmalaw Island]] in southwestern [[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston County]].\n\n==Route description==\nSC 700 begins at a dead end in the town of Rockville on Wadmalaw Island. The terminus is on the north side of Bohicket Creek, which separates Wadmalaw Island from [[Seabrook Island]], a short distance east of Bohicket Creek's mouth on the [[Edisto River|North Edisto River]]. The state highway heads northeast as Maybank Highway, a two-lane road that passes by the [[Charleston Tea Plantation]], the only working tea plantation in the United States, and near the [[Firefly Distillery]], which is on Bear Bluff Road on the portion of the island north of Leadenwah Creek. SR 700 crosses Church Creek onto Johns Island, enters an outlying section of the city of Charleston, and arrives at the main crossroads of the island near the site of the venerable [[Angel Oak]]. Main Road heads north from the junction through the northern part of the island before crossing the [[Stono River]] on the [[John F. Limehouse Memorial Bridge]] to meet US 17 between [[Rantowles, South Carolina|Rantowles]] and Charleston. Bohicket Road heads south toward Seabrook Island and Kiawah Island. SC 700 continues east and near the eastern end of the island intersects River Road, which leads south to [[Charleston Executive Airport]].<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\"/>\n\nSC 700 expands to four lanes and crosses Pennys Creek and the Stono River on the high-level [[Paul Gelegotis Bridge]] and enters James Island. The highway passes through a golf course and along the south side of the historic [[Riverland Terrace]] neighborhood. SC 700 continues into a commercial area where the highway has a [[wye (rail)|wye]]-type junction with [[South Carolina Highway 171|SC 171]] (Folly Road) west of the [[McLeod Plantation]] and Charleston Country Club. Old Folly Road is used for the movements from eastbound SC 700 to southbound SC 171 and from northbound SC 171 to westbound SC 700. SC 700 and SC 171 head north concurrently on Folly Road, which has two lanes northbound and three lanes southbound. The highways enter the [[West Ashley]] section of Charleston by crossing Wappoo Creek, part of the [[Intracoastal Waterway]], on a [[Wappoo Creek Bridge|drawbridge]] named for [[Burnet R. Maybank]]. SC 700 and SC 171 diverge at a directional intersection that does not allow access from southbound SR 171 to eastbound SC 700. SC 171 heads north as Wesley Drive and is used to access southbound US 17 (Savannah Highway) and [[South Carolina Highway 61|SC 61]] (St. Andrews Boulevard). SC 700 heads northeast as five-lane Folly Road (three lanes westbound and two lanes eastbound) to its eastern terminus at a partial interchange with US 17 just west of the U.S. Highway's interchange with SC 61 and its bridges over the [[Ashley River (South Carolina)|Ashley River]]. The interchange allows access between SC 700 and US 17 in the direction of the peninsular section of Charleston.<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\"/>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\"/>|state=SC|county=Charleston}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Rockville\n|mile=0.00\n|road=[[Dead end (street)|Dead end]]\n|notes=Western terminus\n}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Charleston\n|lspan=3\n|mile=18.99\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=south|name1=Folly Road|city1=Folly Beach}}\n|notes=Western end of SC&nbsp;171 concurrency\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=19.96\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=north|name1=Wesley Drive|to2=y|US|17|dir2=south|SC|61|city1=North Charleston|location2=[[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]]}}\n|notes=Eastern end of SC&nbsp;171 concurrency\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=20.38\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=SC|US|17|dir1=north|name1=Savannah Highway|city1=Charleston|city2=Mount Pleasant}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus; southbound exit from and northbound entrance to US&nbsp;17\n}}\n{{Jctbtm|keys=concur,incomplete}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\">{{cite map|publisher=[[South Carolina Department of Transportation]]|title=Highways - Zipped Shapefile of roads maintained by SCDOT - Statewide|url=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/GIS/Statewide_Highways_2012.zip|format=ESRI shapefile|year=2012|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=S+Carolina+700+E&daddr=Folly+Rd&hl=en&sll=32.600952,-80.192868&sspn=0.00442,0.010568&geocode=FVxv8QEdGFU4-w%3BFTQv9AEd2Mg7-w&t=h&mra=ls&z=11|title=South Carolina Highway 700|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\">{{cite web|url=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/default.aspx|title=General County Highway Maps|publisher=South Carolina Department of Transportation|accessdate=2012-05-31}}\n*[http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/County/Charleston_County.pdf Charleston County] (PDF)\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML}}\n{{commonscat}}\n*[http://www.angelfire.com/sc3/scroads/sc700-709.html#sc700 The Highways of South Carolina: SC 700]\n\n[[Category:State highways in South Carolina|700]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston County, South Carolina|South Carolina Highway 700]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston, South Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Mist6820", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Carolina_Highway_700"}
